<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Following are major news items
in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Switzerland's major banks, under increasing international
pressures, have published a list of some 2,000 dormant world War
II-era accounts that may include the assets of Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
-- An Italian military court sentenced Erich Priebke, a German
former SS officer charged with crimes against humanity for his
role in the massacre of civilians in 1944, to 15 years of prison.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Canadian fishermen finally allowed a U.S. ferry to leave
after holding the vessel captive in its berth in a Canadian port
for three days to protest U.S. overfishing of salmon in the
pacific.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. House and Senate GOP leaders and tax writers
reached agreement Monday night on most details of a proposed 85
billion U.S. dollars net tax cut package.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Boeing is close to winning European approval for its 14
billion acquisition of McDonnell Douglas after offering four key
concessions.
</P>
<P>
-- Britain acknowledged Northern Ireland Protestant parties
will block peace talks unless the IRA, which recently declared a
new ceasefire agrees to hand over its weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
