<HEADLINE> EU Approves Boeing-McDonnell Douglas Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BRUSSELS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- After getting promise of
concessions, the European Commission today gave go-ahead to the
planned merger of two giant American aerospace companies, Boeing
and McDonnel Douglas.
</P>
<P>
Karel Van Miert, EU commissioner responsible for competition
policies and the main negotiator on the EU part, told reporters
that he believed this was a successful story of the "solidarity"
shown by the 15 EU member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Approves Boeing-McDonnell Douglas Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The concession could ensure that the U.S. market remains open
to competition from its main European rival, the French consortium
Airbus.
</P>
<P>
Other concessions include maintaining Douglas Aircraft as a
separate subsidiary to minimize Boeing's advantage in bidding for
contracts to replace the aging McDonnell jets in service
worldwide, licensing key patents and intellectual property for
airliner components to competitors, and providing greater details
of government aid to European regulators.
</P>
<P>
"This is a significant step toward completing the merger of
these two great aerospace companies," Boeing Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer Phil Condit was quoted as saying in Seattle
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In another press conference held here on the same day, Richard
A. Albrecht, executive vice-president of the Boeing Commercial
Airplane Group, indicated that Boeing paid more attention to the
"long-term interests" of their customers, suppliers, shareholders
and more than 200,000 employees of Boeing and McDonnell Douglas.
</P>
<P>
The European approval of the deal, valued at around 14 billion
U.S. dollars, has averted the possibility of a damaging
trans-Atlantic trade war centered on Boeing and Airbus.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read out by Van Miert at the press conference,
President of the European Commission Jacques Santer said he was
"satisfied" with the result of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations were reportedly interwined with high-level
political interventions.
</P>
<P>
Last week, U.S. President Bill Clinton threatened trade
retaliation against Europe if the merger was blocked while
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright lobbied on Boeing's behalf
in a call to German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
