<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Reform Higher Education System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- A report from British National
Committee of Inquiry into Higher Education (NCIHE) is published on
Wednesday aiming to reform higher education system and put it at
the heart of national competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
"In the next century, the economically successful nations will
be those which become learning societies,"said the report.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of education is life-enhancing...This recognition
of the purpose of higher education in the development of our
people, our society and our economy is central to our vision,"
added the report.
</P>
<P>
The report recommends that it should be a clear objective of
national policy to be of world class in the business of learning
at all levels and in a range of research of different kinds.
</P>
<P>
The committee seeks to create a new compact between higher
education and society which would mean higher education entering
into specific obligations to students and investing in staff and
students accepting an obligation to contribute more to the cost of
higher education.
</P>
<P>
It would also mean government providing greater stability in
funding and providing the support higher education needs to ensure
it is world class and institutions of higher education building up
partnerships with the social and commercial communities which they
serve.
</P>
<P>
In a wide-ranging and comprehensive analysis of the future
national need for a world class higher education system, the
committee looks to higher education expanding by up to 40 percent
over the next 20 years and proposes tough measures to safeguard
standards.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch of the report, NCIHE Chairman Sir Ron
Dearing mentioned the situation in 1963 when the last major higher
education review launched: "In response to calls to double
participation by the year 2000, it has achieved the target four
years early...It earns 1 billion pounds a year in foreign
exchange."
</P>
<P>
"But, the core issues now are how to ensure that higher
education in this country is world class, adequately funded, cost
effective," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 1700-page report was asked to look 20 years into the future
and to make recommendations on the long list of issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
