<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beiping-Tianjin Campaign Memorial Hall Inaugurated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The Memorial Hall of the
Beiping-Tianjin Campaign, a famous military episode in China's
Liberation War, was formally inaugurated here today.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President and Chairman of the Central Military
Commission Jiang Zemin, Premier Li Peng, and vice-chairmen of the
Central Military Commission Liu Huaqing, Zhang Zhen, Zhang Wannian
and Chi Haotian wrote inscriptions for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
The inscription of Jiang Zemin, also general secretary of the
Chinese Communist Party, reads: Eternal glory to the martyrs who
died heroically during the Beiping-Tianjin Campaign.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng's inscription reads: Strengthen education on
revolutionary traditions, and inspire the people's enthusiasm of
loving the Party and the country.
</P>
<P>
Liu Huaqing wrote: The victory of the Beiping-Tianjin Campaign
represents a great victory in people's war.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wannian, attending the inauguration ceremony, extended
congratulations on the opening of the memorial hall on behalf of
the CPC Central Committee, the State Council and the Central
Military Commission.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said in his speech that though the Beiping-Tianjin
Campaign took place nearly half a century ago, people cherish the
memory of the revolutionary veterans with Mao Zedong as their
leading representative -- at a time when the nation has made great
achievements in building socialism with Chinese characteristics,
</P>
<P>
"The aim of building the memorial hall was to glorify the
historic deeds of the revolutionary veterans and to teach the
younger generation not ever to forget this part of our history,
and to pass on from generation to generation the revolutionary
spirit enriched with the martyrs' blood and lives," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhang stressed that it is an important historic mission for the
country and its armed forces to stride into the 21st century with
a splendid new image.
</P>
<P>
"Let us unite closely around the CPC Central Committee with
comrade Jiang Zemin at the core, and work hard with one heart and
one mind to greet the convening of the 15th CPC Congress," he said.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration ceremony of the memorial hall was presided
over by Li Laizhu, commander of the Beijing Military Area Command.
</P>
<P>
The memorial hall is located by the Ziyahe River in the
Hongqiao District of Tianjin City. It covers an area of 12,800 sq
m.
</P>
<P>
The Beiping-Tianjin Campaign was one of the three massive
campaigns of the Liberation War period, which helped quicken the
pace of China's liberation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Business Leaders Back Britain's EMU Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Britain's business leaders called
on the British government here today to make an early pledge to
take the country into the European Monetary Union (EMU), but
insisted Britain should stay away from the first wave of the
single currency.
</P>
<P>
The Confederation of British Industry (CBI) said in a political
statement that Britain should join a single European currency when
conditions were in place for it to be sustainable, including
inflation and fiscal convergence and flexible labor markets.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that UK's economic and business interest is best
served by membership of EMU under the right conditions. It is
vital for our economic interests that EMU is a success and Britain
must be involved in working for that goal," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
However, the CBI leaders noted that there were "doubts" over
whether the economic conditions for all the potential EMU entrants
would be in place by its planned start date of January 1 1999.
</P>
<P>
Although these business leaders thought it was likely that a
single currency would go ahead on that date, they made it clear
that "It is unlikely that our position in the economic cycle will
make entry on 1st January 1999 -- even if the others go ahead."
</P>
<P>
The CBI statement noted that consultation with its members
nationwide suggested only 6 percent were opposed to Britain's EMU
membership for the foreseeable future with 42 percent in favor of
signing up to the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
