<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SIB Approves New London Stock Exchange Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The Securities and Investments
Board (SIB) today approved plans by the London Stock Exchange to
move to immediate publications of all trades once completed. This
represents a significant increase in transparency.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the Chancellor of the Exchequer, published
today, the SIB said that high levels of transparency were a
foundation for fair and efficient markets and promoted investor
confidence.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the proposed trade publication rules for
securities to be traded on the London Stock Exchange's new
order-driven trading service -- SETS -- should set a framework for
the London Stock Exchange to be as transparent as any leading
equity market in the world.
</P>
<P>
The proposed rules for SETS will require immediate publication
of all trades on execution and establish a new worked trade
regime for very large trades (eight times normal market size).
</P>
<P>
The result of the new rules should: --confirm the London Stock
Exchange as one of the most transparent of the world's leading
equity markets;
</P>
<P>
-- significantly improve the transparency of trading
information and so make for a fairer market;
</P>
<P>
-- provide a new and practical approach to the trading patterns
likely to develop in the new market structure;
</P>
<P>
-- encourage investors to use the new system, enhancing the
liquidity of the order-book and the quality of the price-formation
process.
</P>
<P>
In its report, the SIB states that the freedom that member
firms will have to deal outside the order-book makes it especially
important to ensure that all market users have immediate access to
information on trades once completed, whether on or off the order
book.
</P>
<P>
The SIB welcomes the London Stock Exchange's undertaking to
keep the new regime under close surveillance and to be ready to
make modifications if it is either not working effectively or not
being used as intended.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the London Stock Exchange will keep under review
the need for a minimum size of order which qualifies for trading
on the order-book.
</P>
<P>
The SIB has reached the conclusions set out in its report
following discussions with the London Stock Exchange and informal
but extensive consultation with other interested parties over
recent weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-23 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Passes Bill to Strengthen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 23 (Xinhua) -- In a controversial vote,
Israel's Knesset (Parliament) passed today the first reading of a
bill that requires the majority of 80 votes for giving up the
occupied Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor and Meretz parties cried foul of the way
the vote was conducted, charging the ruling coalition for playing
dirty tricks in order to get the bill passed.
</P>
<P>
The bill, which required the majority of 80 votes for amending
the 1981 law to annex the Golan Heights, passed the first reading
with a vote of 43-40 in a stormy session.
</P>
<P>
The snap vote was called by Likud's Speaker Dan Tichon, who
took advantage of the opposition lawmakers' joy about defeating a
similar bill that required a majority of 60 votes and national
referendum for giving up the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
After the first Golan Heights bill failed to pass the first
reading, the Knesset became chaotic as opposition lawmakers burst
into joyful celebration, some of whom even left the house.
</P>
<P>
At this time, Tichon called a snap vote on the second
bill. And instead of calling the name of every member for their
decision like in the first vote, the speaker decided to conduct an
electronic vote on the second one.
</P>
<P>
The scene was that of Pandemonium as some opposition members
were too jubilant to participate in the new vote and one of them,
Meretz lawmaker Haim Oron even mistakenly voted for the bill.
</P>
<P>
Speaking earlier at the podium, Likud's Justice Minister Tzahi
Hanegbi also played a trick to mislead the opposition by saying
that the government was against the bill. But in the formal vote,
all coalition lawmakers in fact voted for the bill.
</P>
<P>
In protest, opposition lawmakers walked out the Knesset after
the vote to boycott the rest of the session.
</P>
<P>
Shevach Weiss, Labor's former Knesset Speaker, decried today's
vote as "terrible," which he said was unprecedented either in
Israel or any other western countries. Labor leader Ehud Barak
strongly condemned the government for playing dirty tricks.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure from the opposition which demanded for a
second vote on the bill, Tichon late agreed to consider whether to
conduct a re-vote within 24 hours because of "technical reasons."
</P>
<P>
The status of Golan Heights, which was taken from Syria by
Israeli troops in the 1967 War, has been at center of the
disputes between Israel and Syria. Syria is demanding Israel's
full withdrawal from the heights in exchange for a peace treaty,
but Israel's hardline Likud government has stated that it would
never return the whole Golan heights for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between Israel and Syria have been totally
frozen since the Likud government came to power in May last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Jewish Leader Gives Cautious Nod to Swiss Banks' Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 23 (Xinhua) -- A leader of the German Jewish
community today cautiously welcomed today a move by Swiss banks to
run advertisements worldwide in search for heirs to
unclaimed bank accounts left over from the era of World War II.
</P>
<P>
Michel Friedman, an executive committee member of Germany's
Central Council of Jews, said Wednesday that the efforts to find
the heirs to the dormant accounts in Swiss banks came late, "but
better late than never."
</P>
<P>
It was good to finally see Swiss banks playing an active, not
merely a reactive role on the issue, Friedman added.
</P>
<P>
But he also stressed that the move should only be viewed as the
first step by Swiss banks to clarify their own war-time history
and to be responsible for Nazi victims.
</P>
<P>
Swiss banks have come under sharp international criticism since
last year for failing to help trace back billions of dollars of
lost assets presumed to be held by Nazi victims during World War
II.
</P>
<P>
In an unprecedented move, Swiss banks on Wednesday launched an
advertisement campaign in major newspapers around the world
searching for the heirs to the war-time accounts.
</P>
<P>
The money would be paid back quickly after legitimate heirs
have been found and any assets left unclaimed will be given to
charity, said the Swiss banks' advertisements carried by major
newspapers in Germany, France, Britain, the United States, Israel,
South Africa and Eastern European countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
