<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-23 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Rival Community Leaders to Meet Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash will meet here
next Monday to discuss humanitarian matters, said Government
Spokesman Manolis Chistofides at his daily press briefing today.
</P>
<P>
Early today, the spokesman for the U.N. Peace-Keeping Force in
Cyprus Waldemar Rokoszewski announced that a meeting between
Clerides and Denktash will take place on Monday at the residence
of U.N. Resident Representative, Gustave Feissel, situated in the
U.N.-controlled buffer zone in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was agreed upon Tuesday during separate meetings
Feissel had with Clerides and Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Christofides said that the meeting will tackle the issue of
persons listed as missing during Turkish invasion in 1974 and
the plight of a Greek Cypriot teacher, who is prevented from
returning to her home in the Turkish-controlled northern part of
the island by the Turkish Cypriot regime.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the meeting will have an open agenda, the spokesman
said the talks will focus on humanitarian issues but did not rule
out the possibility of discussing confidence building gestures
relating to a specific humanitarian issue.
</P>
<P>
He noted that other meetings may follow after Monday's
encounter, before the two leaders resume their second round of
direct talks in Switzerland, scheduled for August 11 to 16.
</P>
<P>
The first round of U.N.-led direct talks between Clerides
and Denktash took place at Troutbeck, near New York on July
9-12. The two leaders decided to meet in Cyprus to discuss
humanitarian issues.
</P>
<P>
"President Clerides and Denktash will meet on their own on
Monday and possible participation of others at these meetings in
Cyprus will be decided at a later stage," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a Greek Cypriot coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite this
Eastern Mediterranean island nation as bi-communal, bi-zonal
federation through peace talks, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
