<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Resume Arms Sales to Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 23 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will resume
arms sales to Rwanda, a senior official said in Pretoria today.
</P>
<P>
The decision was prompted by the changed circumstances in
Rwanda and the need for the country to restore peace and order,
Kader Asmal, Chairman of National Conventional Arms Control
Committee told the reporters.
</P>
<P>
South Africa suspended its arms export to Rwanda in November
last year pending the return of the stability to the central
African region and after indications that Rwandan armed forces
made cross-border incursions into former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
At that time, South Africa said the suspension would be
reviewed once cross-border violations by Rwanda ceased and a
clear understanding emerged that its armed forces were using
weapons for self-defense only.
</P>
<P>
Local observers noticed that Pretoria made the decision to
resume arms sales to Rwanda after Rwandan Vice President Paul
Kagame visited South Africa early this month when the two sides
pledged to promote comprehensive cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Asmal, also Water Affairs and Forestry Minister, confirmed
that his committee approved last August a contracting application
from arms manufacturer Denel for the sale of a number of advanced
artillery pieces to a Middle East country.
</P>
<P>
However, Asmal, who declined to name the country, noted no
export permit had as yet been approved.
</P>
<P>
According to Asmal, the South African government was to carry
out what he described as a far-reaching policy of maximum
disclosure on arms sales.
</P>
<P>
Disclosure to the general public would include the total value
of contracts, and general descriptions of the weapons supplied.
</P>
</TEXT>
