<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Namibia to Share Stock Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 23 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Johannesburg
Stock Exchange (JSE) and Namibian Stock Exchange (NSE) today
signed an agreement on information sharing here in the capital
city.
</P>
<P>
This is part of a move toward building closer working links
and boosting investment within the Southern African region, JSE
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Today's signing is within the framework of a regional
initiative of cooperation between stock exchanges within the
Southern African Development Community," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement provides for the exchange of information between
exchanges to improve surveillance and protection to their
investors, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
Several companies with large investment in Namibia were listed
on the JSE and dual-listed on the NSE, while many financial
groups and market participants had operation in both countries.
</P>
<P>
JSE President Russell Loubser pointed out that "the successful
development and advancement of independent national capital
markets and especially stock exchanges within our region will
boost the liquidity and efficiency of the markets and attract
more foreign investment."
</P>
<P>
Bob Meiring, Chairman of the NSE Executive Committee, also
spoke highly of the role of JSE, saying the JSE could play an
important part through supporting the development and cooperation
of southern Africa's stock exchanges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
