<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of Uzbekistan,
Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan met today in Bishkek, capital of
Kyrgyzstan, agreeing on an initiative on settlement of the Afghan
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported that the initiative was
proposed by Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev in order to convene a
peace conference on the Afghan conflict in Bishkek this year with
all sides concerned attending.
</P>
<P>
The three foreign ministers reached an agreement on the need to
follow developments in Afghanistan and exchange information for
making joint decisions.
</P>
<P>
They said that the situation in Afghanistan was one of the most
acute military and political problems in Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax quoted Kyrgyz Foreign Minister Muradbek Imanalayev
as saying the Afghan issue has been placed on the agenda of a
summit of the Kyrgyz, Kazakh and Uzbek presidents, which was
scheduled in the town of Cholpon-Ata, the Issyk Kul region of
Kyrgyzstan on July 24.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers also discussed preparations for the Central
Asian Battalion-97 peacekeeping exercises sponsored by the U.N. in
September, to be held on Uzbek and Kazakh territories.
</P>
<P>
They expressed their support for the peacekeepers from the
United States, Denmark, Turkey, Russia, Ukraine, Georgia,
Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia in taking part in the exercises.
</P>
