<HEADLINE> N. Ireland Unionists Vote Against Arms Surrender Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The pro-British unionists today
voted against crucial arms surrender plans, a setback for the
government to make a political settlement to the Northern Ireland
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported that all the three unionist parties had
voted against the plans at peace talks in Belfast this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The government's plan has been rejected," David Adams of the
Ulster Democratic Party told reporters emerging from the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Ireland had proposed that both pro-British and
Pro-Irish guerrilla groups surrender their arms during peace
talks, rather than before or after the talks.
</P>
<P>
Unionist leaders are angry that a new ceasefire by the Irish
Republican Army (IRA) will allow its political wing Sinnn Fein to
participate in the substantial all-party peace talks scheduled for
September without an IRA commitment to surrender its arms. The IRA
truce took effect on Sunday, a crucial step towards a political
solution to the decades-old conflict in the divided province.
</P>
<P>
British Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam said earlier in
the day that the likely defeat of the arms plan by the unionists
was not a disaster but clearly a setback.
</P>
<P>
Political sources said that even if the government loses the
vote, the peace talks on Northern Ireland future could still go
ahead either on a bilateral basis or as "proximity" talks in
separate rooms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
