<HEADLINE> Arab Experts Discuss Combating Desertification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Arab experts debating an
international agreement for combating desertification and its
impact on the Arab world wound up their work here today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 50 experts in agriculture, desertification and land
reclamation from different Arab countries discussed ways to fight
desertification in the Arab world during the two-day meeting at
the Arab League (AL) General Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
They also explored the possibility of increasing the acreage
of cultivable land under an international agreement signed by
most of Arab countries, including Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The agreement signed in Paris, France, in October, 1994 on
combating desertification is aimed at reining in the grave
impact of desertification on fauna and flora worldwide through
enhancing the Arab environmental awareness.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Development Program (UNDP) alerted, in its latest
report, that the Arab region is one of the most parched parts of
the world and that land reclamation operations should be given
maximum priority in Arab countries, Fatmah el-Malah, director of
the Environment Department at the AL told the opening session
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Desertification is considered the gravest environmental
problem menacing the Arab world where large parts of land lie in
the dry and semi-dry zones," she warned.
</P>
<P>
Eleven Arab countries consume mammoth quantities of their
water resources in an irrational way while nine other countries
are suffering a lack of drinkable water, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was convened at a time when a number of Arab
countries, with Egypt in the fore, are exerting diligent efforts
to increase their agricultural areas and cultivate the desert.
</P>
</TEXT>
