<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20 Percent UK People Live in Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Britain's 20 percent population, or
11 million people, lived in poverty in 1990, up from 14 percent or
7.5 million people in 1983, according to a report published today.
</P>
<P>
The study, by Bristol University researchers and MORI, bases
its classification of poverty on a person's access to a list of
items and services which the general public believe as the minimum
necessary for an acceptable way of life.
</P>
<P>
The report, Breadline Britain in the 1990s, finds that 10
million people could not afford adequate housing because their
homes were unheated or damp, or because older children must share
bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
It estimates that 2.5 million children were forced by poverty
to go without necessities such as three meals a day, toys and
school outings.
</P>
<P>
About seven million people went without essential clothing,
such as a warm waterproof coat, and five million were not properly
fed, having only two meals a day or insufficient fresh fruit and
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Around 6.5 million could not afford one or more essential
household items, such as a fridge, telephone or carpets, the
report says.
</P>
<P>
More than two-thirds of respondents said that the government
was doing too little to help to alleviate poverty and the report
also blames poverty for inequalities in mental and physical
health.
</P>
<P>
The poor were more likely to feel isolated, to be depressed and
to feel looked down upon. They were more likely to have a
long-standing illness or a disability, it says.
</P>
<P>
The survey concludes that Britain has become an increasingly
polarized nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
