<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Abortion Rate up 8.3 pct in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The number of abortions carried out
in Britain rose to 177,225 last year, an increase of 13,587, or
8.3 percent, on 1995, according to figures released today by the
Office of National Statistics (ONS).
</P>
<P>
The rise is the first time in five years and although there
were increases in every age group up to 44, it was highest among
teenagers in the age group of 16 to 19-year-olds, at 15.2 percent,
with a total of 28,746 abortions.
</P>
<P>
There was a rise of 11.3 percent in abortions undergone by
girls under 16 last year, from 3,270 to 3,639.
</P>
<P>
Among older women aged 35 to 39, the increase was 12.1 percent,
giving a total of 16,086 abortions in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The findings made family planners call for an urgent review of
contraceptive services to determine whether they are meeting
women's demands.
</P>
<P>
The Family Planning Association said it was "very concerned"
about the disappearance of family planning clinics.
</P>
<P>
Life, the pro-life charity, said the figures were "deeply
shocking" and what the government should be doing is thinking the
whole of current sex education theory and practice instead of
pouring money into condom and abortion agencies.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Health Department said: "We are not sure
why the figures have gone up and the Office of National Statistics
is undertaking a review. We have to look at this in the longer
term to see if there is a changing pattern or if this is a one
year blip." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
