<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Attacks Israeli Patrol in S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's Hezbollah guerrillas
announced that they launched an attack today on an Israeli patrol
in south Lebanon, killing and wounding several Israeli soldiers,
but Israel denied any casualties were caused to its forces.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, the Islamic Resistance, military
wing of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, announced that
one group of its fighters carred out the attack at Wadi Al-Slouki
in the Israeli self-proclaimed "security zone" earlier this
morning.
</P>
<P>
The guerrillas used machine-guns and rocket-propelled grenades
in the attack, "leading to the killing and wounding of several
elements of the Israeli forces," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli army spokesman confirmed the pre-dawn guerrilla
operation in the buffer zone, but denied that any casualties were
caused to the Israeli occupation forces.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah also announced that its Shiite Muslim fighters
attacked today a patrol of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army
(SLA) militia on the road between Beit Yahoun and Konin in the
border strip.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli occupation forces did not stop their daily
bombardment, and fired seven 155mm artillery shells today at
suspected guerrilla targets on hills opposite the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
Israeli jets also dived down from the blue sky over Beirut
around 11:00 a.m. local time (0800 GMT), making an explosive
noise by breaking sound barrier.
</P>
<P>
Twelve Israeli soldiers have been killed and nearly 50 others
wounded in clashes with Hezbollah in south Lebanon since this
year, reminiscent of a battlefront between Israel and its Arab
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state established the 1,100-square-kilometer
"security zone" in 1985 in an attempt to protect northern Israel
from cross-border attacks by Lebanese militants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
