<HEADLINE> Turkey's D-8 Policy to Continue: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkey announced today that it
would continue to push forward the D-8 Group movement which was
initially launched by former prime minister Necmettin Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a weekly news briefing, Turkish Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Omer Akbel said that the D-8 Group was part of Turkey's
state policy rather than that of the government.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 Group, which consists of Turkey, Iran, Egypt, Nigeria,
Pakistan, Bangladesh, Malaysia and Indonesia, was established at
the initiative of Erbakan, who was regarded as a pro-Islamic prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question, Akbel quoted Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem as saying that the Turkish government attached
importance to the D-8 Group.
</P>
<P>
"It is of our interests how D-8 Group would be used and
implemented for the benefit of all concerned countries," said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Akbel told the briefing that there was no plan for the time
being to admit Turkic republics to the bloc of developing Muslim
nations.
</P>
<P>
He, however, added that new Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and
other cabinet members attached great importance to the Central
Asian regions.
</P>
<P>
The D-8 Group summit was held in Istanbul, the largest city of
Turkey, just three days before the June 18 resigning of the
Erbakan-led coalition government.
</P>
<P>
There are rumors here that the D-8 Group will end up
with nothing definite since the Yilmaz government might not be
so interested in the policy that the former government had
pursued.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that though the current government
pledged its adherence to the Muslim bloc, no efforts as great as
the Erbakan administration did could be expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
