<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-23 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tunisian Parliament Passes Ninth Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The Tunisian National Assembly
passed today the Ninth Five-year Development Plan (1997-2001),
aimed at achieving a 6 percent annual growth rate compared
with 4.6 percent in the previous one.
</P>
<P>
Parliament sources said that Tunisian Minister of Economic
Development Taoufik Baccar delivered a speech at the start of the
parliamentary session, revealing the outlines of the plan and
future expectations to make Tunisia to the same level as advanced
countries by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Baccar said the plan aims not only to achieve a favorable
growth rate, but also to consolidate the country's economic
structures and potentials.
</P>
<P>
With regard to external financing of the plan, the minister
indicated that a significant portion of the required funds can be
obtained, citing the good intentions expressed by Tunisia's
financial partners during the recently-held international
symposium in Tunis on the prospects of financing the plan.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the growth rate during the period, the Tunisian
minister asserted that the annual growth rate of 6 percent in the
coming five years may be achieved through a growth rate
of 4.3 percent in the agricultural sector, and a rise in other
non-agricultural sectors from 5.8 percent to 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the role of the private sector, Baccar said the
implementation of the new five-year plan depends on the
integration of the private and public sectors.
</P>
<P>
He said the private sector is to take care of production,
creation of job opportunities and investment, adding that it
will contribute 56 percent of the total projected
investments in the plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
