<HEADLINE> House Speaker Calls for End to Leadership Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Newt Gingrich, speaker of U.S.
House of Representatives, on Wednesday called for ending turmoil
in the Republican Party over his leadership.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly encourage every Republican to participate in this
dialogue," Gingrich said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Let me emphasize: I will not allow another chapter to be
written in this tiresome and overwrought saga. This discussion
will be the end of the story," he said.
</P>
<P>
He issued the statement before a closed-door Republican
conference originally designed to discuss strategy for passage of
balanced budget and tax cut bills, central goals of the party for
this congressional session.
</P>
<P>
But the meeting was overshadowed by the leadership issue, which
has plagued the Republican-controlled House since reports surfaced
last week of an attempt to oust Gingrich by dissatisfied members
-- including some leaders -- who felt he had lost the political
initiative to President Bill Clinton, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
The 228 Republican House members have also been called by
Gingrich to another meeting on Wednesday evening to "hold a family
discussion on how we can continue to move our party forward as a
family."
</P>
<P>
In his statement Gingrich said, "We must ensure that every
member understands both the responsibilities of leaders of the
conference and the equally important and commensurate
responsibilities of the members of this conference."
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday Gingrich asked members not to seek the resignation
of any leaders who might have been involved in the attempt to oust
him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
