<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cyprus' trade deficit for the first three months of
1997 fell by 7.9 percent to 279.2 million Cyprus pounds (about
558.4 million U.S. dollars), compared with 303.1 million pounds
(606.2 million dollars) in the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the Department of Statistics and
Research, released here today, total imports, comprising imports
for home consumption and imports placed in bonded warehouses,
decreased by 8 percent to 423.1 million pounds (846.2 million
dollars), compared with 459.9 million pounds (919.8 million
dollars) in the first quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, total exports fell by 8.2 percent to 143.9
million pounds (287.8 million dollars), compared with 156.8
million pounds (313.6 million dollars) in the first three months
of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has remained the Cyprus' major market,
receiving 29.9 million pounds (59.8 million dollars) or 55.6
percent of Cyprus' domestic exports, excluding ship's stores.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries constitute the second largest market for
Cyprus' goods with a share of 22.2 percent of its export, or 12
million pounds (24 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Switzerland has decided to offer Egypt up to 100
million Swiss Francs (147.5 million U.S. dollars) in a
consolidated funding, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Half of the funding will be in the form of a non-refundable
grant and the rest will be in loans to finance services and
development projects in Egypt, the MENA report said.
</P>
<P>
But details of the funding will be worked out at negotiations
with an Egyptian delegation in the Swiss resort of Berne next
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth Swiss funding to Egypt. The previous three
funding agreements totaled an estimated amount of 300 million
Swiss francs (442.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- The Tunisian National Assembly passed today the
Ninth Five-year Development Plan (1997-2001), aimed at achieving
a 6 percent annual growth rate compared with 4.6 percent in the
previous one.
</P>
<P>
Parliament sources said that Tunisian Minister of Economic
Development Taoufik Baccar delivered a speech at the start of the
parliamentary session, revealing the outlines of the plan and
future expectations to make Tunisia to the same level as advanced
countries by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Baccar said the plan aims not only to achieve a favorable
growth rate, but also to consolidate the country's economic
structures and potentials.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the growth rate during the period, the Tunisian
minister asserted that the annual growth rate of 6 percent in the
coming five years may be achieved through a growth rate of 4.3
percent in the agricultural sector, and a rise in other
non-agricultural sectors from 5.8 percent to 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Baccar said the implementation of the new five-year plan
depends on the integration of the private and public
sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
