<HEADLINE> U.S. Regrets Vote on Disarming in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. said today it
regretted a vote by Northern Ireland unionist parties against
disarming guerrillas in the British province.
</P>
<P>
Three unionist parties in Northern Ireland voted earlier today
against proposals by the British and Irish governments that the
Irish Republican Army and the pro-British guerrillas groups should
both disarm while taking part in peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"We regret that vote," State Department spokesman James Foley
told reporters. "I think the important point, though, is that the
process will continue," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The British and Irish governments have expressed commitment to
this process leading to a negotiated settlement. We don't see this
vote as an end of that process," Foley said.
</P>
<P>
The IRA called a ceasefire at the weekend which will admit its
political wing, Sinn Fein, to the talks in September if Britain
deems the truce genuine. 
</P>
