<HEADLINE> French Foreign Minister to Visit Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine will pay a visit to several Middle East countries by the
end of August or in early September.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine told Radio-Television Luxembourg (RTL) this afternoon
that he will visit Egypt, Israel, Palestine, Jordan, Lebanon,
Libya and Syria.
</P>
<P>
"This is an important occasion to see exactly where we are as
regards this peace process which is clearly stalled, and what
France can be of use, in close liaison with its European partners,
to give substance to this process again," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would "listen, better understand, and perhaps
give proposals later" instead of giving "revealed truth" to the
leaders of the countries once engaged in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
On the talks held on Tuesday between Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy, Vedrine said that
"the only useful element is that they meet each other."
</P>
<P>
The talks between Arafat and Levy did not bring any concrete
result. Levy said after the meeting that Israel does not plan to
freeze its project to build housing in an Arab district of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli plan to build the settlement has paralyzed peace
talks between the two sides since March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
