<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Gas Vehicle Fleet Launched in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Britain today launched its largest
fleet of natural gas vehicles and a filling station to serve them.
</P>
<P>
The fleet, including 9 small vans, 9 buses and 6 trucks, were
produced by a partnership of gas utility Centrica plc, joint
venture Iveco Ford and the Energy Savings Trust.
</P>
<P>
Gas vehicles were cleaner to run, produced less noxious
emissions, and were quieter, said Peter Lehmann, Commercial
Director of Centrica.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch, Environment Minister Michael Meacher
said the most challenging objectives in the program involved
reducing levels of nitrogen dioxide and particulates. Natural gas
vehicles produce less of these emissions than conventional
vehicles, he added.
</P>
<P>
But there are two main barriers, the high cost of vehicles and
the lack of infrastructure for refuelling, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Meacher told reporters that Prime Minister Tony Blair had
ordered the conversion of his family car to run on liquefied
petroleum gas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
