<HEADLINE> Angolan President Warns of Imminent Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Eduardo dos
Santos warned here today of another military conflict that's
likely to break out soon in the country.
</P>
<P>
Santos made the first ever open remark since the regional
fights loomed nationwide, while meeting his visiting Namibian
counterpart Sam Nujoma.
</P>
<P>
He said that people should be realistic in realizing the war
that's likely to break out, but the government would try hard to
avoid any armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
The National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) have unilaterally suspended the Lusaka Peace Accord
signed in 1994, and thus ushered in worries of another civil war,
the president said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the UN observer group should do their best to
help keep the peace process continue in the country.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Namibian president said that he wished the
Angolan government and UNITA to observe the Lusaka Peace Accord
and avoid further military actions.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma arrived in Angola this morning for a brief visit aiming
to discuss the bilateral trade cooperation issues. 
</P>
