<HEADLINE> Women Urged to Be United at African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The women's assembly at the
African African-American summit taking place in Harare today
called on African governments to take steps to let women to work
together, protect children from abuse and enhance women's
position in the society.
</P>
<P>
The assembly was addressed by, among others, Coretta Scott
King, wife of the slain U.S. black civil rights activist Martin
Luther King, and Botswana first lady Gladys Masire.
</P>
<P>
Masire said there was need for governments to analyze all
policy programs to establish their effects on women, many who
continued to be discriminated against and lived in abject
poverty.
</P>
<P>
''Our governments should stimulate economies that create
opportunities and employment for women and guarantee ownership of
land to women and improve their access to credit,'' said Masire.
</P>
<P>
King, who received a standing ovation for her speech, said
women had a crucial role in creating a non-violent environment
for children to grow up in.
</P>
<P>
She encouraged the teaching of conflict prevention and
management to children so that they could live in a peaceful
world while girl children needed to be taught self-confidence and
to be peace makers.
</P>
<P>
She said, ''The primary cause of violence is the decadence of
moral values in society. We must teach our children correct
values and we must lead an exemplary life.'' 
</P>
