<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Urges Closer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
today called for increased economic ties between Africa and the
United States when he officially opened the Fourth African
African-American Summit here in the capital.
</P>
<P>
"Africa needs a strong partnership with America which will
embrace trade, investment, cultural and other forms of closer
cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Such cooperation should assist in the development of vibrant
economies in Africa, perhaps in a much shorter period than most
of us might imagine," Mugabe told delegates to the four-day
summit started on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Africa's new struggle is now focused on
rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 delegates from Africa, America and Europe
attended the summit, including Senegalese President Abdou Diouf,
Botswana President Ketumile Masire, Ethiopian President Meles
Zenawi, Angolan Prime Minister Van Dunem and Gabonese
Vice-President Didjob Divungi Bi Ndinga, Secretary General of the
Organisation of African Unity Salim Ahmed Salim.
</P>
<P>
Leon Sullivan, convener of the summit described the meeting as
a milestone in the progress of African-African American unity.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the continent as the last frontier of
development, he implored the U.S government to become more
actively involved in Africa's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Senegalese President Abdou Diouf, who ceded chairmanship of
the summit to Mugabe, commended U.S President Bill Clinton for
his initiative of "partnership for growth and economic
opportunities for Africa" which will allow certain African goods
to enter the American market duty free.
</P>
<P>
"We also praise the involvement of most industrialized
countries gathered at the Denver summit from June 20 to 22 to
place Africa and its development at the center of world agenda,"
Diouf added. 
</P>
