<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Georgia to Achieve Lasting Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today said that the primary responsibility for revolving the
differences in the Georgian/Abkhaz issue and finding a lasting
political settlement rested with the Georgian and Abkhaz sides.
</P>
<P>
In a message at the opening of the three-day Georgian/Abkhaz
talks in Geneva, Annan said that assistance, economic support and
the peacekeeping force could come from others in the international
community, but it was up to the two parties themselves to develop
direct dialogue and to make the necessary compromises to achieve a
lasting settlement.
</P>
<P>
During this process it was essential that the two sides
maintained their commitment to the non-use of force or threat of
the use of force against each other, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the United Nations had been involved in the
Georgian/Abkhaz peace process for four years and had been
physically present on the ground with military observers since
August 1993, joined later by the Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS) peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
While the military situation in the area had remained
relatively stable, there had been little progress in finding a
lasting political settlement, he added.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the current talks should mark a continuous
process of contact, exchange and negotiation to resolve this
painful conflict.
</P>
<P>
The three-day Georgian/Abkhaz talks are chaired by Liviu Bota,
special representative of the UN secretary-general. Participants
include Foreign Minister of Georgia Irakli Menagarishvili, head of
the Abkhaz delegation Sergei Shamba, Russian Ambassador Lev
Mironov, Ambassador Michael Libal for the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe and representatives of the
Friends of the Secretary-General on Georgia, namely Britain, the
United States, France, Russia and Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
