<HEADLINE> OAU Asks U.S. to Build True Partnerships with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Africa needs genuine partnerships with
countries such as the United States to help build its economy,
secretary general of the Organization of African Unity Salim Ahmed
Salim said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing delegates at the opening ceremony of the fourth African
African-American summit, Salim said although Africa was adjusting
itself to play meaningful role in the global economy and to become
self sufficient, it was aware of the need of foreign assistance.
</P>
<P>
''We expect a genuine partnership to come from the U.S.. Africa is
prepared and has committed itself to transform its economy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
''Let's work together to give Africa a chance. Let's double our
efforts to build a new image of Africa and to help Africa become an
equal partner in the global village,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Salim said the establishment of the African Economic Community
(AEC) showed the seriousness of the continent to improve itself.
</P>
<P>
The AEC launched at the OAU summit in Harare in June held its
first trade and investment meeting in Mauritius recently where a
series of measures to promote foreign investment in Africa were
formulated.
</P>
<P>
Salim said africa's image as a continent for conflicts, hunger and
poverty was slowly changing, and it was through such summits that
this was being made possible.
</P>
<P>
The majority of African countries were now enjoying peace,
security and relative stability and most were registering modest
economic growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added, ''African leaders have committed themselves to moving
forward with the process of democratization, good governance and
respect human rights.'' 
</P>
