<HEADLINE> Turkish Military Criticized for Intervening in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's True Path Party (DYP)
today obscurely criticized the military for intervening in party
politics, saying Turkey needs no "savoirs."
</P>
<P>
The DYP, led by former deputy prime minister Tansu Ciller,
made the remark in a statement issued here following a two-day
high-level meeting of the party.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the forced termination of the former coalition
government by the army a month ago, the statement pointed out that
this result would be not only harmful to the present but also to
the future.
</P>
<P>
It is very unfortunate that the Turkish people have to protect
the country's democracy although the country has a
half-a-century-long multi-party politics, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the guarantee of the country's democracy was
the republican system itself, the statement noted that the
Republic of Turkey needed no "savoirs" at all.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that the DYP criticism was apparently
directed against the military led by Chief of General Staff
Ismail Hakki Karadayi, which forced the former Necmettin Erbakan
government to step down.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military, which describes itself the defender of
Turkey's secularism and democracy, held that the Erbakan
government would encourage the growth of the fundamentalism,
which was termed as the fatal threat to the republic.
</P>
<P>
"As is very much the case for our religious beliefs, no one has
the right or power to exploit our republic for political
considerations, " said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It also rebuffed the spy accusations that Ciller had been
working as an agent for the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency
(CIA), describing it as "unprecedented" in the history of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The General Staff has reportedly ordered a probe into the
alleged Ciller agent case initially launched by Dogu Perincek,
Chairman of the Workers' Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
