<HEADLINE> Greece Welcomes US Resolution on Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government today hailed a
U.S. House of Representatives resolution on the Cyprus problem as
"very positive."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the U.S. resolution called for the
demilitarization of the divided island and the withdrawal of the
35,000 Turkish occupation troops.
</P>
<P>
If the points contained in the resolution constituted active
elements of U.S. foreign policy, then a permanent and viable
solution of the Cyprus problems could be attained, Greece's
government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said today.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that similar texts had in the past been
adopted by representatives bodies of the United States, but they
were not implemented in the country's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and occupied northern Cyprus in the wake of a Greek Cypriot coup
engineered by the then military junta ruling Greece.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash recently held their first round of direct talks in
Troutbeck, near New York, for a solution to the protracted Cyprus
problem. They are expected to hold another round of talks in
Switzerland in August. 
</P>
