<HEADLINE> First Palestinian Flight Arrives in Amman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The first flight by Palestinian
Airlines arrived here today, thus starting once-in-two-week
Palestinian flights between al-Arish, Egypt and Amman.
</P>
<P>
On board were 34 passengers, including director general of
Palestinian Civil Aviation Authority (PCAA) Fayez Zaidan and some
other Palestinian officials, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
The maiden flight should have taken off from Rafah, the Gaza
Strip, but finally started from al-Arish due to restrictions
and obstacles placed by the Israeli government, said Zaidan upon
arrival at the Queen Ali International Airport here.
</P>
<P>
Before the end of the summer, Palestinian commercial flights
are also expected to reach Turkey and Saudi Arabia, the
director general added.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Greece, Turkey, Cyrus and Jordan are the
only countries in the region that have agreed to allow Palestinian
Airlines to operate to and from their territories.
</P>
<P>
The PCAA decided to launch the route from al-Arish, near
Egypt's border with the Gaza Strip, after Israel refused to let
them open a new airport in Rafah in the southern tip of the
strip. 
</P>
</TEXT>
