<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Fighting in Hubei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hubei Province has
aroused 800,000 people to fight flooding caused by torrential
rains from July 12-16.
</P>
<P>
Some 45 counties and cities in Hubei had more than 100 mm of
rainfall, and three had as much as 300 mm during the period.
</P>
<P>
Water levels at some sections of the Yangtze River and 28 of
the large and medium-sized reservoirs have exceeded the danger
mark.
</P>
<P>
Flooding has struck plains and lakeside areas, toppling nearly
40,000 housing apartments and inundating 740,000 ha of
farmland. It has caused a direct economic loss of 1.4 billion yuan
(168.67 million US dollars) and victimized 7.64 million people.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government organized the task force to reinforce
embankments, discharge flood water and relocate flood victims.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,600 pumps have been used to discharge water from
flooded farmland.
</P>
<P>
Reservoirs in Hubei have taken in 3.2 billion cubic meters of
flood water to alleviate the pressure on the lower reaches of the
Yangtze. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Defense Chief Proposes Scrapping Youth Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- French Defense Minister Alain
Richard today proposed the abandoning of the newly adopted
obligatory defense training program for youths under 18, called
"Citizens' Rendez-vous."
</P>
<P>
Richard told the daily Le Monde published today that he plans
to replace "Citizens' Rendez-vous" with a one-day "preparation"
lesson to inform the youths about their country's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of abandoning the five-day obligatory defense
training could reduce the high costs which will result from
gathering all of the country's youths above 16 for medical
checkups and travels as are required by the program.
</P>
<P>
The French government is desperately fighting to cut the
country's high public deficit to meet the criteria for joining the
European single currency.
</P>
<P>
Richard also suggested that programs be provided for the youths
who volunteer to join more sophisticated military trainings, so as
to establish a reserve force for the French army.
</P>
<P>
The former French National Assembly adopted in February the
bill on "Citizens' Rendez-vous," which was aimed at storing up
medical, social and professional information of French youths,
helping handicapped youths to better integrate into the society,
and encouraging youths to engage in volunteer jobs at home and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac declared in February 1996 that
France would abandon its 200-year conscription practice by 2001,
as it no longer fits the present security and defense needs.
</P>
<P>
Under conscription, all French youths are required to serve in
the army for 10 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
