<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Jobless Claims Last Week Lowest in A Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The number of American workers
filing first-time claims for jobless benefits declined last week
to the lowest level in nearly a year, U.S. Labor Department
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that new applications for unemployment
insurance totaled a seasonally adjusted 299,000 during the week
ended July 19, lowest since the week ended July 27, 1996. The drop
of 42,000 followed an even larger 45,000 decline the previous
week.
</P>
<P>
Much of the huge decrease may have been due to auto plants
reopening after their annual new-model retooling and the end of
auto strikes.
</P>
<P>
The weekly jobless claims in the U.S. are quite volatile, but
if they were to persist at around 300,000, it likely would be a
sign of tightening labor markets in the country. And a tight labor
market could raise inflation fears if employers were forced to
raise wages to attract qualified workers and were able to increase
prices to cover the added expense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
