<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Forge Stronger Ties with Africa: Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. president Bill Clinton today
renewed his country's commitment to forge stronger and more
constructive ties with Africa.
</P>
<P>
In a letter handed to Zimbabwean president Robert Mugabe by
U.S. secretary for transportation Rodney Slater, Clinton said the
African African-American summit had taken place at a time when
his country was renewing its commitment to forge closer ties with
the continent.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe was touring stands at the trade and investment
exposition which runs concurrently with the summit.
</P>
<P>
The four-day summit which began on Tuesday presented another
forum for the U.S. and Africa to expand their ties and work
towards mutual objectives, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "my announcement on June 17 along with a bipartisan
group from congress of our intent to pass legislation that will
forge new economic and commercial ties to African countries
pursuing growth oriented reform policies underlines our interest
in pursuing dynamic partnerships with African countries that are
working to build their own futures.''
</P>
<P>
Clinton said opening markets, increasing investment, improving
technical skills, decreasing debt burdens and encouraging growth
oriented reforms were important elements for helping African
nations grow and reap the benefits of economic integration.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., he said, was encouraged by the numerous positive
changes in Africa, especially the adoption of democratic and
economic reforms by many countries.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the Denver summit had committed themselves to
support African efforts to promote democracy and good governance,
Clinton said, including improving public institutions and
strengthening civil society.
</P>
<P>
They had also agreed to improve access to markets for African
exports and support its integration into the world economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mugabe said during the tour that although the
summit was being hosted here, the benefits would be reaped by the
whole southern African Development Community (SADC) region, and
he reiterated his call for Americans to invest in the continent.
</P>
<P>
While he encouraged them to invest in the continent, he hoped
they would invest in southern Africa as this would enhance the
capacity to develop the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
