<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets former US President Carter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
today told former US President Jimmy Carter that maintaining and
developing a healthy and stable Sino-US relationship is necessary
for world peace and prosperity in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting here today with Carter, Jiang praised the
ex-president for his contributions to the bilateral ties, while he
was in office and after his term as president.
</P>
<P>
The main reason the diplomatic relations were established between
China and the United States nearly two decades ago is that the
Chinese and US leaders at that time were aware of the vital common
interests existing between the two countries, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Despite great changes in today's international situation, he
noted, the common interests between the two great countries, China
and the US, in maintaining world peace, and promoting economic
growth and social progress are expanding rather than diminishing.
</P>
<P>
Since early this year, Jiang said, the Sino-US relations have
steadily improved and expanded. He added that the current
bilateral ties are experiencing an important opportunity for further
growth.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that China and the US would continue to
make concerted efforts to build a long-term stable and healthy
bilateral ties with an eye to the 21st century by increasing
mutual trust and strengthening cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Carter said the US-China ties are of great importance, and that
the two countries share the responsibility of promoting world
peace, security and development, and should forge a partnership
based on mutual understanding and trust, he added.
</P>
<P>
It is very important to intensify mutual understanding, Carter
emphasized, and the US should try to understand China from an
objective point of view and acquaint itself with China's
development.
</P>
<P>
Carter described Jiang's state visit to the United States this
fall as a major event in US-China relations.
</P>
<P>
Carter told Jiang that his trip to China is meant to realize
the initial objective of forging of diplomatic ties between the
two countries: To bring about the sustainable and all-round growth
of bilateral relations between the US and China.
</P>
<P>
He said he will continue to work for this end.
</P>
<P>
Carter and his party were invited by the Chinese Institute of
Foreign Affairs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
