<HEADLINE> Central Asian Leaders Discuss Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Presidents of Uzbekistan,
Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan met in the Kyrgyz resort of Cholpon-Ata
today to discuss integration among the three countries, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders will discuss plans to set up an
inter-parliamentary union and determine the status of the Central
Asian peace-keeping battalion made up of servicemen of the three
nations.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit is being held in the framework of the
Central Asian Union of these former Soviet republics, formed three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also discused the situation in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev suggested a peace conference be
held in Bishkek under the auspices of the United Nations in a bid
to resolve the armed conflict in the country. 
</P>
