<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian NGO Slams Israeli Decision on Golan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A Cairo-based non-governmental
organization today strongly denounced the move taken Wednesday by
the Israeli parliament to maintain occupation and settlements in
the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
The Afro-Asian Solidarity Peoples' Organization (AAPSO), in a
statement, described Israeli Knesset's approval of the draft bill on
banning withdrawal from the occupied Syrian territory as an
"irresponsible, provocative and serious move."
</P>
<P>
It is a flagrant violation of the principles of international
law and all relevant United Nations and Security Council
resolutions, said AAPSO in the statement carried by the Egyptian
MENA news agency.
</P>
<P>
"Such aggressive measures call for more tension and
instability: something that can trigger a blow-up in the region,"
the statement said, adding that Israel must take the blame for
this.
</P>
<P>
The organization also voiced full support and solidarity with
Syria in "claiming its absolute right to restore the Golan up
to the borders of June 1967 and have all settlements dismantled
so that just and overall peace materializes in the area."
</P>
<P>
The bill's text stipulates that a decision to withdraw from the
strategic plateau must be approved by a two-thirds majority, or 80
MPs out of the 120-member Knesset.
</P>
<P>
The bill, approved by 43-40 votes at Wednesday's first reading,
must pass three readings in parliament before it becomes law. It
was proposed by an MP from the ultra-nationalist Tsomet party and
supported by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and most of his
ministers.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Syria and Israel have been on ice since
February last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
