<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Skyscraper Designers Learn from Ancient Chinese Pagodas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Mushrooming skyscrapers, a symbol
of the prosperous real estate business of this financial center of
China, will be dwarfed by a pagoda-shaped highrise when its
construction is finished next year.
</P>
<P>
The 88-story Jinmao Mansion has reached its 85th story at
present. Its final height of 420.5 meters will make it the tallest
building in China.
</P>
<P>
The building, to house offices and hotels, is located in the
Lujiazui Financial and Trade Zone in Shanghai's Pudong New
Area. It is designed after an ancient Chinese pagoda, whose
separate stories diminish in size as they get higher.
</P>
<P>
The US architectural firm SOM, designer of the giant tower,
adopted such a shape in order to make it resistant to strong winds
and earthquakes, after studying a number of ancient Chinese
pagodas.
</P>
<P>
The project costs 500 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some other major Chinese cities, such as Guangzhou, Chongqing
and Beijing, are also planning to construct buildings over 100
stories high.
</P>
<P>
The 68-story and 384-m-high Diwang (King of the Land)
Commercial Mansion in south China city of Shenzhen holds the
height record in the country at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
