<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwanese Tourists Increase Sharply to Xiamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The latest statistics show that
Xiamen, a port city of east China's Fujian Province, has seen a
sharp rise in tourists from Taiwan, to reach some 60,000
passengers in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The figure is up 37 percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Fujian is the ancestral home of most Taiwanese, and Xiamen,
which has much in common with Taiwan, is now one of the five major
ports through which Taiwanese enter the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan government lifted the ban on Taiwanese to visit the
inland provinces in 1987; about 1.7 million Taiwanese had visited
the city by the end of last year, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
"The number of Taiwanese tourists still keeps increasing, and
the trend has never been reversed, even when the relations between
the straits were strained in the past," they said.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwanese investment in the city has also maintained a stable
growth over the past few years, totalling 2.9 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The sources say that Taiwanese investors have built 1,375
projects in Xiamen, accounting for nearly one fourth of the total
investment they have made in the inland provinces.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Xiamen's economy has been driven up, and many
hotels have been built because of the quick growth of its tourist
industry.
</P>
<P>
Taiwanese businessmen have bought many houses in the city over
the past year, the sources say.
</P>
<P>
A sample survey shows that nearly one third of the total
Taiwanese tourists to Xiamen stay with their local relatives, or
with Taiwanese friends.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
