<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Ministers Call for Greater Effort to Face </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 24 (Xinhua) -- the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) today took great pride the
achievements the grouping has made in the past 30 years, but
called for greater efforts to do even better in facing future
challenges.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 30th ASEAN Ministerial Meeting, which opened
here this morning, Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon
said, "The ASEAN has exceeded all its early expectations as a
model for regional cooperation and consensus in promoting peace,
stability and security."
</P>
<P>
He noted that ASEAN has led in the establishment and management
of the ASEAN Regional Forum. "Our leadership within this critical
regional body reflects the international recognition, credibility
and respect that the ASEAN has won in the arena of regional
security affairs."
</P>
<P>
However, Siazon stressed that as ASEAN approaches the 21st
century, "it must re-tool itself, drastically if necessary, so as
to deal more effectively with old and new challenges."
</P>
<P>
He urged the development of more growth areas in the region,
which he said "has immense potential, due to its rich natural
endowments, its sizeable markets and its talented people..."
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas in his speech called for
gearing ASEAN economic cooperation toward making the enlarged
ASEAN "a more closely integrated, dynamic and prosperous entity."
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that "with the solid progress the ASEAN
has achieved over the past three decades, we can now face the new
century, the new millennium with justified confidence."
</P>
<P>
"I believe we can sustain the spirit that has carried us this
far, the ethos of harmony and consensus-seeking, consultation and
compromise, cooperation and partnership and a keen sense of what
is realistically achievable at every point of our journey
forward," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In doing so, we shall remain faithful to our basic principles
and ideals that have enabled us to be masters of our own destiny
and active contributors to the making of a better world," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Foreign Minister S. Jayakumar attributed ASEAN's
success to five principles: sovereign equality, non-interference
in each other's internal affairs, concern over the use of force to
change an established government or an internationally recognized
political order, open economies and all the members having made
ASEAN the cornerstone of their foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
The political coherence and cohesion that ASEAN has achieved by
adhering to the five principles "has given the ASEAN a significant
voice in the international community," he said, adding that "our
ability to remain steadfast to these principles will be a major
factor to keep the ASEAN a strong and vibrant organization."
</P>
<P>
Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasan said on the occasion
that ASEAN's experience shows that "we can indeed make a
difference."
</P>
<P>
"While we can look back with satisfaction, we must continue to
strive forward to keep pace with a world that is undergoing great
transformation due to the forces of globalization," he declared.
</P>
<P>
He urged ASEAN to develop "an outward-looking policy that
responds to our needs and our potential."
</P>
<P>
"Because of our success, we will be expected to play a more
active role in global affairs," he said. "It is timely therefore
to examine how we can contribute to the international community,
not only for the benefit of our region, but also for other
developing nations."
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh Cam noted in his speech
that with the upgrading of India, China and Russia to its full
dialogue partners last year, ASEAN now has dialogue partnership
with all big powers in the world. "This is also an important
turning point in ASEAN external relations and a new element
serving the interest of peace and stability in the region."
</P>
<P>
Brunei Foreign Minister Mohamed Bolkiah pointed out that
ASEAN's past "has been productive," "the present is under sound
management" and "the future is very largely ours to construct."
</P>
<P>
"We have shown ourselves able to create impressive regional
initiatives but a strong emphasis in our work now... will be
firmly placed on their practical application," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
