<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Former Japanese Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, July 24 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin, in a
meeting with visiting former Japanese Prime Minister Morihoro
Hosokawa here today, said that the present sound relations between
the two countries have not been easy to achieve.
</P>
<P>
He added that good bilateral relations have been achieved
through the hard work of several generations of people in both
countries, and need to be cherished.
</P>
<P>
Extending a welcome to Hosokawa, who visited China three years
ago, Jiang said that with joint efforts by the two governments and
friends from all walks of life in the two countries, bilateral
relations have developed remarkably since the normalization of
relations 25 years ago, bringing major benefits to both sides.
</P>
<P>
"We should express our thanks to those who made major
contributions to the promotion of friendship between the two
peoples and to bilateral relations," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Citing China and Japan as two influential countries in the
region and in the world as a whole, Jiang said the establishment
and development of good-neighborly and cooperative relations
facing the 21st century are not only in the fundamental interests
of the two countries, but will also make positive contributions to
peace, stability and development in the region and in the world as
a whole.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that as long as the two sides adhere to the
principles set out in the Sino-Japanese Joint Declaration and the
China-Japan treaty of peace and friendship, and handle bilateral
relations from a longstanding and strategic viewpoint, our
relationship will continue to grow in a healthy and stable way,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that history can serve as a mirror from which
historical lessons can be drawn, saying, "We have held that the
development of friendship between the two peoples can be continued
from generation to generation on the basis of accurate knowledge
of history and with a view to the future.
</P>
<P>
He praised Hosokawa for his clear attitude toward history
during his term as Japanese prime minister, noting that his
courage in facing up to history shows his far-sightedness.
</P>
<P>
Hosokawa said that, generally speaking, bilateral relations are
progressing well, and that the two countries have set up sound,
stable, friendly and mutually-beneficial ties with an eye to the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
An accurate understanding of Japan's invasion of China in the
past is the basis for the further enhancement of bilateral
relations, the former Japanese leader said, noting that the war
brought China great sufferings, and Japan must reflect on this.
</P>
<P>
Taking into consideration the general situation of bilateral
relations and looking to the future, the two countries can
overcome a number of problems that they are facing so as to raise
their relationship to a new height, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
