<HEADLINE> U.S. to Work With Thailand, ASEAN on Cambodian Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Special Envoy on Cambodia
Stephen Solarz said here today that his country hopes that all
those Cambodians who are now in exile could return and participate
in the election next year.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting with Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh
at the government house today, Solarz told reporters that the
United States "wants to work very closely with Thailand and other
members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in
seeking a solution to the Cambodian problem."
</P>
<P>
He said the Thai prime minister and he "had a very constructive
exchange of views."
</P>
<P>
"I think that we see the problem in very similar terms," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy added that they both hope that the Cambodia
problem can be resolved in agreements, which will make genuine
national reconciliation in Cambodia possible.
</P>
<P>
Agreements on the Cambodia problem will lead to "a truly and
genuinely free and fair election next year under circumstance
where all those who are now in exile are in a position to return
and to participate fully in the political life of the country,"
Solarz said.
</P>
<P>
Though fully aware of the difficulties of achieving a
satisfactory solution, Solarz said he was hopeful that if the
U.S. and other countries around the world can work closely with
ASEAN in the effort to resolve this matter, success may ultimately
be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Solarz is leaving for Phnom Penh later today. 
</P>
