<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Displaces 200,000 in Northern Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 200,000 people were
displaced due to recent heavy fighting in the Shomali Valley
north of Kabul in Afghanistan, a UN mission here said in a report
today.
</P>
<P>
The UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) office said that
the latest sharp increase in the displacement has been caused by
intense fighting which led to the Taliban losing the key town of
Charikar to fighters of the northern anti-Taliban alliance over
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Shomali Valley, an important agricultural region stretching
from Kabul into the surrounding Hindu Kush mountains, has been
largely depopulated by continued fighting and forced displacement.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR said that while many of those who left the region did so
to escape fighting, tens of thousands of others were ordered to
leave from their homes by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
A number of those who have fled Shomali have entered Pakistan
and registered with UNHCR as refugees.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Iran's Interior Ministry declared that it has
adopted the measures to deal with the influx of refugees from
war-torn Afghanistan and northern Iraq and it will only accept
refugees whose lives are in danger.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Ali Mohammad Besharati said Wednesday that
Iran is hosting over 2 million foreign refugees and Iran
pursues the policy of treating foreign nationals in humanitarian
and Islamic manner.
</P>
<P>
Besharati complained that assistance from international relief
agencies for refugees in Iran has been insufficient. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Crisis Threatens Stability of Indian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The recent split of the Janata
Dal and the subsequent disputes over the status of its breakaway
wing plunged the 13-party ruling United Front into a serious
crisis, threatening the stability of the three-month-old Indian
government led by Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral.
</P>
<P>
The split of the Janata Dal occurred on July 5 after a fierce
power struggle took place within the party which was then the
dominant constituent in the United Front.
</P>
<P>
The major cause leading to the split, the worst setback for the
United Front since its formation in May last year, can be traced
back to a previous political crisis triggered by the withdrawal of
support to the H.D. Deve Gowda government by the Congress party on
March 30.
</P>
<P>
Having failed to muster enough support to form its own
government after forcing Gowda to resign as prime minister on
April 12, the Congress party offered to compromise with the United
Front to avert a premature mid-term poll.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party said it would renew its support to a new
United Front government to be headed by anyone other than Gowda.
</P>
<P>
However, Gowda, backed by the left parties including the Indian
Communist Party of India (Marxist), refused to step down from the
United Front leadership, insisting that the Congress party either
support the front unconditionally or face a mid-term poll.
</P>
<P>
In order to break the deadlock and avert a snap poll, Bihar
Chief Minister Laloo Prasad Yadav, the then president of the
Janata Dal, came out to suggest that Gowda should step down as
parliamentary leader of the United Front to pave the way for a new
patch-up with the Congress party.
</P>
<P>
Much against his will, Gowda resigned as parliamentary leader
of the United Front which later chose Gujral, minister of external
affairs in the Gowda team, to succeed him.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the installation of the Gujral government, the
Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) decided to charge Prasad
Yadav with alleged involvement in a scandal in which huge sums of
public funds earmarked for purchasing fodder were embezzled in
Bihar state between 1985 and 1991.
</P>
<P>
Gowda, resentful of Prasad Yadav's role in his dumping and
Gujral's ascendance to premiership, seized this opportunity to
retaliate.
</P>
<P>
On the one hand, he joined the chorus with the left parties and
the opposition Bharatiya Janata Party to demand the resignation of
Prasad Yadav from the post of Bihar chief minister.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he backed the then Janata Dal working
president Sharad Yadav to contest against Prasad Yadav in the
party's organizational poll scheduled for July 4 to elect a new
party president.
</P>
<P>
In defiance of huge pressures for him to resign, a cornered
Prasad Yadav boycotted the party poll on July 4 and floated his
own party, the Rashtriya Janata Party (RJD), the second day, while
his rival Sharad Yadav became president of the truncated Janata
Dal.
</P>
<P>
The Janata Dal, which used to be the largest constituent in the
United Front with 45 seats in the Lok Sabha (the lower house of
parliament), was reduced to the second place in the front with
only 27 Lok Sabha seats compared to the 33 seats held by the
Communist Party of India (Marxist).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Crisis Threatens Stability of Indian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The split of the Janata Dal, however, did not bring to an end
the troubles that endangered the stability of the Gujral
government.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the split, Prasad Yadav announced that his
party supported the Gujral government and wanted to stay in the
ruling United Front.
</P>
<P>
This, as expected, was flatly rejected by Gowda, the Janata Dal
and left parties which not only insisted on keeping the RJD out of
the front but also urged Prime Minister Gujral to remove the three
ministers nominated before by Prasad Yadav.
</P>
<P>
Gujral, whose power base was seriously weakened following the
split in the Janata Dal, took pains to strike a balance when
dealing with the conflicting requests from within his United
Front.
</P>
<P>
While giving clear signals that he was strongly against
corruption, Gujral refused to bow to pressures from Prasad Yadav's
rivals who urged him to use his capacity as prime minister to
force the resignation of the chief minister or impose the
presidential rule in Bihar.
</P>
<P>
Beware of the danger of internal strife to the fragile
coalition government, M. Karunanidhi, Tamil Nadu chief minister
and president of the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK), came to the
rescue of Gujral and Prasad Yadav on July 14 by threatening to
withdraw his party's four ministers from the government and only
support it from outside.
</P>
<P>
In a clear reference to Gowda, Janata Dal President Sharad
Yadav and left parties leaders, he accused some United Front
leaders of having formed a coterie within the front and using the
front to settle their own personal scores.
</P>
<P>
Vowing to control the suicidal tendencies of certain
constituents in the front, he said he favored the entry of the RJD
into the front and the continuance of the three ministers in the
Gujral government though they are loyal to Prasad Yadav.
</P>
<P>
He warned that his party would take a final decision on its
withdrawal from the United Front government on July 27 if and only
if the front did not set its house in order.
</P>
<P>
However, Karunanidhi's virulent attack failed to dilute the
tough approaches adopted by Gowda, the Janata Dal and the left
parties towards Prasad Yadav.
</P>
<P>
At a crucial meeting of the United Front leaders held on July
17, the parties concerned failed to settle their disputes over the
entry of the RJD and the continuance of the three ministers loyal
to Prasad Yadav, and decided to take a final decision on these
issues on July 25.
</P>
<P>
Pending the July 27 deadline set by the DMK, the United Front
leaders will meet here tomorrow to iron out their differences over
issues resulted from the split of the Janata Dal.
</P>
<P>
Despite all their bickering, the rival parties may now be ready
to agree on a temporary truce for the survival of the coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
Whatever comes out of tomorrow's meeting of the United Front
leaders, the current crisis triggered by the split of the Janata
Dal has already seriously undermined the unity of the front, and
its future development will undoubtedly have a profound impact on
the Gujral government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
