<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nominations for Consultative Council in Oman Due </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Nomination for Oman's
Consultative Council, which will include women, will be held in
mid-October, the Omani news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Nominations for the Consultative Council, known in Arabic as
Majlis al-Shura, would take place on a "single day" in the middle
of October throughout Oman's 59 provinces, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The 80-member council is elected through nominations by
civilian and religious dignitaries and tribal and village elders.
</P>
<P>
Oman's Sultan Qaboos in June issued a landmark decree
allowing women across the country to stand for election to
the council, a consultative body seen as an important sounding
board for public opinion.
</P>
<P>
The sultan's directive also enabled women to nominate
candidates for the council. After the nominations, Sultan Qaboos
has the final say in picking the 80 candidates.
</P>
<P>
During Oman's last Consultative Council elections in 1994, the
government granted women living in the capital of Muscat the
right to stand for election and make nominations, but their
participation was limited to the capital's six provinces.
</P>
<P>
In an unprecendented move in the Islamic country, Sultan Qaboos
appointed two of the nominated women to the council in November
1994.
</P>
<P>
Oman announced the creation of the council in 1991 in an effort
to widen representation in the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
