<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fashion Town Emerging on Former Opium-Burning Site of Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Local residents of Humen
township like to point out that while Tokyo responds to the latest
fashion trends from Paris in 15 days, and Hong Kong starts copying
the Parisiennes' styles in about 25 days, Humen beats with the
pulse of Paris fashion, via Hong Kong, in just about a week.
</P>
<P>
With a total of 520 clothing-manufacturing plants, including
320 overseas-backed ones now making garments in Humen, a "fashion
town" is taking shape in the township famed as the site of an
historic opium-burning episode during the Sino-British Opium War
of 1840.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with garment-making manufacturing, more than 50 mills
have also been built for cloth weaving, printing, finishing work,
bleaching and dyeing in the township, located in south China's
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Humen has a population of 90,000 and has 100,000 transients.
More than 40,000 people are employed in the garment making
industry, while 12,000 people are engaged in clothing marketing.
</P>
<P>
Humen now makes 62 million garments a year. Manufacturing
plants produce more than 1,000 styles of clothes each month.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of owners of famous foreign fashion brands
have given licences to have garments made that bearing their name;
others have started their own garment-making businesses in Humen.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, clothing-manufacturing businesses
yearly contribute 100 million yuan in taxes to Humen.
</P>
<P>
Zhong Ganquan, head of the township, said the garment-making
industry has been chosen as the township's new force with which it
can realize its goal of establishing a multi-industrial structure
and advance local economic development.
</P>
<P>
The rapid expansion of the garment-making industry has advanced
development of transport and communication services, tourism,
finance, information, catering and entertainment businesses in the
township.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, the township, which receives 5,000
businessmen from outside its borders daily, has attracted 550
million U.S. dollars of overseas investment. And 1,300 businesses
here are producing goods for overseas market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
