<HEADLINE> China to Increase Cooperation with CPDD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Dr. Stephen G. Holtzman, chairman
of the US College on Problems of Drug Dependence (CPDD), visited
the Ningbo Drug Withdrawal Center Wednesday and expressed his hope
for increased cooperation with the Center.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the Center have attended the annual session
of the CPDD for three successive years, representing China.
</P>
<P>
Yang Guodong, director of the center, has invented an effective
method to help drug users abandon their addiction relatively
painlessly.
</P>
<P>
"Yang's way is wonderful," Holtzman commented.
</P>
<P>
Yang's "One Plus One Method" has proved to be more effective
than many others after six years of clinical tests on nearly 6,000
patients, medical experts say.
</P>
<P>
Drug users treated with Yang's method will never have to rely
on any other kind of drug after they give up using heroin. This
has long been a problem bedevilling overseas experts can not
handle, they say.
</P>
<P>
The Center is to sent some of its staff members to the CPDD for
further training, and the two institutes will also conduct
exchanges in basic research information and materials in the field.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the State Commission of Science and Technology
has decided to build the Ningbo Drug Withdrawal Research Center
into an international training center for doctors trying to help
addicts quit their dependence on drugs.
</P>
<P>
"Drug use is a worldwide problem, and the research personnel in
China and the U.S should increase cooperation in this field," Yang
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
