<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Sees Positive Signs in Russian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian economy has shown signs of
growth, said Russian Prime Minister Victor Chernomyrdin at a
cabinet session today.
</P>
<P>
The industrial output over the past 12 months rose by 2 percent
from the same previous period of last year, Russian media quoted
the prime minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The revenues and expenditure of the Federal government amounted
to 64 percent and 68 percent respectively of the targets set for
the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said that the inflation rate over the period from
January to May was only 7 percent, less than half of that of the
corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
The annual interest rate of national bonds dropped from 180
percent to 20 percent last year, helping attract funds to
investment in production.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin also indicated several negative economic signs,
including the increase of the proportion of arrears in gross
domestic product from 15 percent to 27 percent over the past 12
months.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Russia's trade relations with the European Union
(EU), Chernomyrdin threatened to impose retaliative quotas on
textiles and other imports from the EU unless it lifts similar
restrictions on Russia.
</P>
<P>
The EU posted 44 billion U.S. dollars worth of trade with
Russia last year, which accounted for 40 percent of Moscow's total
foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Russia is losing about 250 million dollars in export revenues
annually due to the EU limits on Russian exports, the ITAR-TASS
news agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
