<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Meet Former Japanese Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today China and Japan should make concerted efforts to ensure a
healthy and stable growth of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with former Japanese Prime Minister Morihoro
Hosokawa, Li said China pursues a good-neighborly policy, and
values the Sino-Japanese ties.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral relations are sound on the whole, Li noted. He
pointed out that there are still problems existing between the
two countries, such as how to properly deal with their history.
</P>
<P>
Li said Chinese leaders have from time to time referred to a
well-known Chinese saying to describe their relationship with the
Japanese: "Past experience, if not forgotten, is a guide for the
future."
</P>
<P>
This is not groundless, he pointed out, because there are
indeed some people in Japan, though not many, who insist on
believing in an inaccurate view of history and try to undermine
the Sino-Japanese ties by reversing the actual events surrounding
Japan's invasion of China.
</P>
<P>
Doing this not only meets with opposition from the Chinese
people, but also is unpopular at home, the Chinese premier said.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed the hope that the two countries will work together
to maintain a healthy and stable development of their relations by
strictly abide by all the principles guiding the two-way ties.
</P>
<P>
In regard to China's situation, Li said, the Chinese leadership
with Jiang Zemin as the core is consolidated and strong, and
successfully handles domestic and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said after the smooth return of Hong Kong to the motherland
on July 1, the Chinese people are working to greet the convention
of the 15th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party with
outstanding achievements in various undertakings.
</P>
<P>
He said that China will resolutely follow the road of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics charted by Deng Xiaoping.
"We are confident of what we are doing," he said.
</P>
<P>
Among leaders of all previous Japanese governments and
Japanese statesmen, Li pointed out, Hosokawa is the one who made
an early and correct assessment of Japan's invasion of China.
This was praiseworthy, he added.
</P>
<P>
Li said he hopes Hosokawa will continue to work to step up the
development of the Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Hosokawa said he stated candidly during his last official visit
to China as prime minister three years ago that the invasion and
war waged by Japanese militarists brought great sufferings to the
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed at the time that this declaration of his
position, which was then met with opposition, was correct, and he
said he has no regrets about saying it.
</P>
<P>
Hosokawa said he came to China with the belief in mind that it
is beneficial to developing the bilateral ties and educating the
future generations to think about and learn from an accurate
account of history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
