<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dam Project to Tame Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Xiaolongdi Dam Project will
control formerly disastrous annual flooding on the Yellow River,
known as the "Sorrow of the Chinese Nation".
</P>
<P>
The multipurpose dam project, located 40 km northwest of
Luoyang, an ancient city in central China's Henan Province, is
scheduled for completion in October this year.
</P>
<P>
The dam will guarantee the safety of 78 million people and 7.3
million ha of farmland in the lower reaches of the river where
raging flood waters often flow at rates as high as 40,000 cubic
meters per second.
</P>
<P>
According to a hydraulics expert with the Yellow River Water
Resources Committee under the Ministry of Water Resources, the
project will greatly enhance flood prevention efforts along the
river, and will raise the possibility of the worst flooding
expected every 60 years to one such flood every 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
The project's key flood control status centers on its
geographical positioning at the end of the last gorge in the
middle reaches of the Yellow River which flows through nine
provinces and autonomous regions. Some 694,000 sq. km., or 92.3
percent, of the Yellow River drainage basin is upstream from the
Xiaolongdi Dam site.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the project, the largest of its kind on the Yellow
River, has a maximum storage capacity of 12.65 billion cubic
meters. In addition, the project has 5.1 billion cu. m. live
storage capacity for sedimentation control.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the project has the capacity to adjust water flow
rates in different seasons to feed the Sanmen Gorge Reservoir some
130 km downstream, as well as the Luhun and Guxian reservoirs
located on a Yellow River tributary.
</P>
<P>
The dam project is expected to save an estimated 1.1 billion
yuan in flood control costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Okays $1.6 Bln Dollar Soft Loan for Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Expressing satisfaction over the
structural reforms by the Pakistani government, the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) has agreed to provide 1.6 billion dollars in
soft loan to the country, a senior IMF official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The first installment of the loan under the blend of Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility and Extended Fund Facility would be
released soon after the approval by the IMF Executive Board, Paul
Chabrier, leader of a visiting IMF mission, told a joint press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Chabrier, who is also IMF Director of the Middle Eastern
Region, said a new culture is being introduced in the wake of
structural reforms in various sectors including banking, taxation
and tariffs.
</P>
<P>
An "efficient system is to be put in place," he said.
</P>
<P>
The measures and changes introduced by the government were
aimed at determining the direction of the economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz told the same news
conference that "we have reached an agreement on the main elements
of the Policy Framework Paper (PFP) which is a requirement of the
Fund and will be signed soon."
</P>
<P>
"This will be formalized before its presentation to the
Executive Board of the Fund," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
The structural reforms and "revolutionary measures" taken by
the government had provided the basis for the IMF loan facility,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Policy Framework Paper would be then presented to the IMF
Managing Director before being to the Executive Board of the IMF
for consideration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
