<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou's Baiyun Airport to Be Relocated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Relocation of Guangzhou's Baiyun
Airport has been given final clearance, as the project has
received approval from the State Council.
</P>
<P>
The new site for the airport -- to be called the Guangzhou
Baiyun International Airport -- is at the junction of
Guangzhou's Baiyun District and its suburban Huadu City. The
construction will begin within the year.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to cost about 20 billion yuan (about
2.4 billion US dollars). Both an expressway and an elevated
railway will be built to link the airport to the downtown area of
Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Located 28 km from Guangzhou City proper and covering 16,000
ha, the new airport will be 1,270 ha larger than the present one.
</P>
<P>
The new airport will be able to accommodate 80 million
passengers and 2.5 million tons of cargo annually. It will have
three runways -- one 4,000 m long and the other two 3,700 m long
each.
</P>
<P>
The floor space will be 280,000 sq m, ample for the terminal to
accommodate 10,000 passengers during peak hours. Upon completion
of first phase, including construction of two runways in 2005, the
new airport will be able to handle 27 million passengers and
740,000 tons of cargo annually.
</P>
<P>
Local leaders have pledged to go all out to streamline the
building of the new airport.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou is one of busiest air traffic hubs in China, with
Baiyun Airport handling 12.644 million passengers last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
