<HEADLINE> Get-together of Leading Economists Highlights Asian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Nobel laureates and 200
distinguished economists from all over the world will share their
insights into the Asian economic panorama at a three-day
international conference, which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The academic gala is the Far Eastern Meeting of the Econometric
Society, one of the world's most prestigious societies for
economists. It is highly honorable to obtain the fellowship of the
Society, which has taken in 18 Nobel Prize winners.
</P>
<P>
As president of the Econometric Society, Professor Robert E.
Lucas of the University of Chicago, 1995 Nobel Laureate, gave an
address today entitled "Inflation and Welfare".
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Hong Kong Department of Economics, the Chinese
University of Hong Kong and the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, it is the largest international conference ever held in
Hong Kong for economists, who have shaped economic research and
government policies.
</P>
<P>
Professor Lawrence Klein of the University of Pennsylvania, who
picked up the Nobel laurel in 1980, will speak at a symposium
Friday, which focuses on the strategic development of the economy
of Hong Kong as part of China after 1997. In a following session,
participants will discuss the continuing growth of East Asian
Economies in the next century. 
</P>
