<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ICRC, WHO Call for Attention to TB in Prisons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee of the
Red Cross (ICRC) and the World Health Organization (WHO) have
joined forces to focus world attention on tuberculosis (TB) in
prisons, the ICRC said in a press release Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
TB experts from Azerbaijan, Georgia, Russia and representatives
from other agencies concerned had a meeting recently in Baku,
Azerbaijan. A declaration issued at the end of the meeting
sponsored by the ICRC and WHO called on governments around the
world to take steps to improve health care for prisoners and
provide adequate treatment for those suffering from TB.
</P>
<P>
"Tuberculosis in prisons easily spreads into the community from
infectious prisoners and infectious prison staff," the declaration
pointed out. "If there is no response to our call for action,
incurable tuberculosis will increase deaths among prisoners and
their families, and prison staff and the community."
</P>
<P>
The declaration warned that the threat of TB was compounded by
two other factors, the spread of HIV in prisons, which increases
the risk of death from TB, and the development of drug-resistant,
often incurable forms of TB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
