<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Continue Peace Efforts for Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan today vowed to carry on
its efforts to broker peace among the Afghan warring factions and
regretted the recent outbreak of fighting in the war-ravaged
country.
</P>
<P>
"The fighting will have no impact on our determination to
continue with the shuttle mission and we are determined to promote
the intra-Afghan peace process," Foreign Office spokesman Khalid
Saleem told a weekly press briefing here today.
</P>
<P>
He said the objective of Pakistan's on-going shuttle diplomacy
was to bring protagonists within the negotiating range, and then
to convene an intra-Afghan dialogue the outcome of which can be
guaranteed by the countries bordering Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Some progress has been made and the proposal of the formation
of a joint political commission to discuss future government in
Afghanistan "is emerging as a distinct possibility," he said.
</P>
<P>
Saleem stressed the need for taking confidence building
measures by the Afghan Taliban militia and their rival side to
pave the way for starting a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was closely coordinating its efforts with Iran and the
U.N. Special Mission on Afghanistan on the Afghan issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few days, the Taliban and anti-Taliban forces
were engaged in fierce fighting north of Kabul. Forces loyal to
former Afghan military chief Ahmad Masood, one of the most
powerful warlords opposing the Taliban, have recaptured the
strategic Bagram airbase, about 50 km north of Kabul, and are
closing in on the beleaguered Afghan capital.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
