<HEADLINE> Cambodia Expresses Desire to Join ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia Foreign
Minister Ung Huot Thursday expressed the desire to join the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said at the ASEAN Ministerial Meeting
(AMM) here, "the Kingdom of Cambodia identifies its future with
countries in the region, especially with the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations-ASEAN."
</P>
<P>
"The joining would give us the necessary incentive to further
combine our efforts for the fulfilment of the vision of ASEAN
founding members, namely the establishment of ASEAN 10," he added.
</P>
<P>
"The goal set by Cambodia to join the ASEAN is the wide
aspiration of the Cambodian people to be part of the family," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia, whose admission to the regional grouping has been
deferred because of the factional fighting in the country, enjoys
observer status in the ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot said that his country "remains confident in its
consistent efforts to restore the national economy and hereby to
integrate itself into the mainstream of the region, the ASEAN."
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that Cambodia will certainly bring positive
contribution to regional peace, stability and economic
development," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister denied that the battles on July 5 and 6, which
resulted in the ouster of First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh,
were neither between Ranarriddh and Second Prime Minister Hun Sen
nor between their two parties.
</P>
<P>
He also declared that the situation in his country has returned to
normal.
</P>
<P>
He announced that Norodom Sihanouk will remain as the king; the
constitution will remain unchanged; the principles of liberal
democracy and pluralism will be adhered to; all international
agreements and conventions signed between 1991 and 1997 will be
respected; and the Cambodian National Assembly will be reconvened on
July 28.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government in Phnom Penh is committed to
organizing "the free and fair general election as scheduled" for May
1998. 
</P>
