<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donors Pressure Serbs to Turn Over War Criminals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BRUSSELS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A two-day international donor
conference on Bosnia held here Wednesday warned the Serbs that they
might be denied aid because of their failure to hand over indicted
war criminals.
</P>
<P>
Hans van den Broek, EU commissioner responsible for relations
with Central and Eastern European Countries and chairman of the
conference, said that aid could not be justified to parties who
"oppose and frustrate" the goal of post-war reconciliation in
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
The EU, which is leading the conference with the World Bank,
said that the Serbs must turn over the war-crimes suspect Radovan
Karadzic before it resumed aid. The EU supplies nearly half of the
reconstruction aid to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
According to the Dayton peace accord, the parties vowed to turn
over those indicted by the United Nations International Criminal
Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek said that "it would be irresponsible to continue
spending public funds for reconstruction purposes" because of the
"overall political and economic influence" of the suspects. But he
added that humanitarian aid to Republika Srpska, as the Bosnian Serb
entity is known, would be continued.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Serbs reportedly said in a statement Monday that they
did not have high expectations of help from the conference.
</P>
<P>
Governments and organizations Wednesday pledged around 1.1
billion U.S. dollars in aid. Sources said that the aid would be
used to support industry, repair infrastructure and fund projects
to get the local economy moving. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
