<HEADLINE> Talks for S. Leonean Crisis Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The meeting on the Sierra Leonean
crisis scheduled for tomorrow will be postponed till next
Tuesday, according to Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi.
</P>
<P>
The Committee of Four on Sierra Leone, made up of Nigeria,
Ghana, Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire, would meet on Friday the
delegation of Sierra Leone's military government to seek ways to
settle the crisis in the troubled west African country.
</P>
<P>
But the meeting has been postponed till next Tuesday, Ikimi
said late Tuesday after consultations with his counterparts on
the panel in Conakry, Guinea, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of the four countries on Tuesday met first
with Guinean President Lansana Conte and then with ousted Sierra
Leonean President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, who has been in Conakry
since fleeing his country following the coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the ministers briefed Kabbah on the
meeting they held last week in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, with the
delegation from Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Clashes in the country, where a cease-fire was agreed at last
week's meeting, have left more than 250 people dead.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, famine and epidemic of alarming proportions have
begun to threaten the country due to the isolation imposed by the
international community since the coup.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of the Red Cross, one of the few
humanitarian organizations still in the troubled country, has
expressed concern that food is becoming scare and unafordable,
while most hospitals have run out of drugs, with fuel for
vehicles fast running out.
</P>
<P>
For weeks, many businesses have remained closed as the
military junta which seized power by force continue to be
isolated by the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
