<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Witnesses Abnormal Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- North China has experienced an
extended period of sweltering heat, with south China continuing to
enjoy cool days.
</P>
<P>
While south China's Guangdong Province has characteristically
recorded hot summer temperatures, Guangzhou recorded a temperature
reading of only 22.8 degrees centigrade on July 13. The city's
lowest summer temperature since 1951 was recorded following 12
consecutive days of heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
North and northeast China, which in the past have experienced
much cooler summers than southern areas, remain in the grips of an
extended heat wave.
</P>
<P>
The 38.2 degree centigrade reading in Beijing on July 13
represented the highest summer temperature on record since
1972. Brisk sales of brand name air conditioners fueled by the
heat wave have created a shortage on the Beijing market.
</P>
<P>
The coastal Tianjin City recorded a July 13 temperature of 39.9
degrees centigrade and residents in the northeast city of Harbin,
nicknamed the "Ice City", are reeling under abnormally high
temperatures hovering between 35-36 degrees centigrade.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Guangdong meteorological Department attribute
to abnormal weather patterns to the appearance of "El Nino" in the
Pacific Ocean.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
