<HEADLINE> Israel Bombards Guerrilla Targets in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli forces bombarded this
morning suspected guerrilla targets of the pro-Iranian Hezbollah,
or Party of God, in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The bombardment came in an apparent retaliation for wounding an
Israeli soldier in the south Lebanon buffer zone earlier this
morning, security sources said, but they did not elaborate on
casualties.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli forces fired 155mm shells from 9:30 a.m. (0630
GMT) at Iglim Al-Toffah, or Province of Apple, a ridge some 60
kilometers southeast of the Lebanese capital Beirut, which is
often used by Hezbollah guerrillas as a springboard to launch
attacks on the Israeli self-proclaimed "security zone" in southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops in the position of Gantara also swept its
vicinities with heavy machineguns, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
In a surprise move, the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army
(SLA) militia shelled this morning the Lebanese army unit
clearing land mines on the road near the Kfar Falous crossing 15
kilometers east of the south Lebanese port city of Saida.
</P>
<P>
It was the first attack targeting the unit since the
commander of the SLA militia, Antoine Lahd, gave his assurance
last week that he would allow the reopening of the crossing
between Saida and the occupied Christian-town of Jezzine on the
north border of the buffer enclave.
</P>
<P>
After a period of calm following last week's surge of
violence in the south, the conflict began to pick up again
Wednesday with two roadside bombs, one against an Israeli patrol
and another a SLA patrol, in the border strip.
</P>
<P>
The Voice of the South Radio, organ of the SLA, confirmed
this morning that four of its militiamen were wounded in the
operations, for which Hezbollah claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah spearheads a guerrilla warfare in south Lebanon in
a bid to oust the Israeli occupation forces out of the Lebanese
land.
</P>
<P>
Israel established a 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone"
in 1985 ostensibly to protect northern Israel from cross-border
attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
