<HEADLINE> Arafat, Levy Disagree on Result of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BRUSSELS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy and the Palestinian president, Yasser Arafat, disagreed
Wednesday over whether a meeting between them had broken the logjam
in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who talked about achieving "significant and positive
steps" at the meeting held in Brussels Tuesday, said Wednesday that
"nothing was achieved yesterday" while Levy said the meeting had
given new impetus to the talks.
</P>
<P>
Both men reportedly made their remarks respectively after
separately meeting with Belgian Foreign Minister Eric Derycke on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat urged the European Union to use its influence on Israel
to further the peace process, saying that he hoped to achieve
"something concrete".
</P>
<P>
He said, "We are not asking for the moon, we are asking the
European Union to help get results. It is very important that with
their help we can save the peace process."
</P>
<P>
The peace talks, which first started in Oslo in 1993, have been
stalled since March this year when the Israelis began building some
6.500 houses in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
However, Levy Wednesday reportedly ruled out the possibility of
suspending the building project. 
