<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congestion Surcharge Imposed at Chittagong Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Feeder vessel operators at
Bangladesh's largest port Chittagong have decided to impose a
congestion surcharge on containers beginning from August 15, local
newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Chittagong Feeder Trade Committee (CFTC), a Singapore-based
organization of feeder vessel operators, has decided to impose
congestion surcharge at the rate of 150 U.S. dollars on 20 feet
containers and 300 dollars on 40 feet containers, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
But the decision was opposed by Chittagong Port
Authorities(CPA), which said the practice would cause another set
back for Bangladesh's maritime trade.
</P>
<P>
The CPA is expected to send a delegation to Singapore next
month and request the CFTC to withdraw its decision, port sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's leading trade bodies have also expressed deep
concern at the CFTC decision, saying it would seriously affect the
trade and industry.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued by those trade bodies said that the
proposed surcharge would put some major foreign currency earners,
such as garment and frozen food industry, in a most incompetitive
position.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that Chittagong was facing problems of "frequent
work-stoppages and go-slows by port workers due to political
instigation, outdated container handling equipment and lack of
adequate container space".
</P>
<P>
The trade union leaders called upon the government to take
measures to improve port services to reassure feeder vessel
operators, port users and private firms.
</P>
<P>
The congestion surcharge was proposed not long after Chittagong
suffered a serious vessel jam earlier this month following a port
workers' strike.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore-based feeder operators had imposed congestion
surcharges off and on from 1992 as a result of shortage of
container handling equipment and space in container yards and
unusual strikes.
</P>
<P>
The CFTC's latest congestion surcharge was in September 1995,
but was lifted on July 1, 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Sets up New Free Trade Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government has decided to
set up a new free trade zone (FTZ) in the southern port city of
Bushehr, according to a local daily here today.
</P>
<P>
The Persian daily Salam reported that the Supreme Council
on Industrial-Commercial Free Trade Zones, headed by President
Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani, decided to turn Bushehr into a FTZ.
</P>
<P>
But the decision has to win approval of the Parliament before
it is officially turning into a free trade zone in accordance
with the law.
</P>
<P>
Bushehr FTZ will be established with the help from
Bushehr's General Governorate Office and the Shipping and Ports
Organization, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
Bushehr will be Iran's sixth FTZ. It will have an advantage
over other Iranian FTZs because it is connected to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Another Iranian FTZ called Chabahar at the coast of sea of Oman
is also connected to the mainland but does not have the vast
port facilities of Bushehr.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the FTZs are either situated in inner lands such
as Sarakhs in northeastern Iran or Sirjan in south-central Iran,
or they are islands in the Persian Gulf such as Qeshm and
Kish.
</P>
<P>
Bushehr port city has historically been used for import and
export. It is at equi-distance from such countries as Kuwait,
Saudi Arabia, Qatar and Bahrain in the southern shores of
the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The report by Salam indicated that Bushehr is well equipped to
be a FTZ because "it enjoys port facilities, infrastructural
networks such as good roads, industrial township and such
amenities as water and electricity."
</P>
<P>
Strategically located at the northern coast of the Persian
Gulf, Bushehr is also home to a large contingent of Iran's naval
forces. The port city has become internationally known in recent
years for its controversial nuclear power plant which is being
constructed there with the help of Russian experts.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Israel have alleged that Iran is seeking to use the
atomic plant for military purposes. Israel has threatened to
stage preemptive air raid against the nuclear facility before
it goes on stream. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
