<HEADLINE> Egyptian Lawyers Sue Netanyahu for Desecration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 24 (Xinhua) -- In a professional way to vent their
anger and frustration, three Egyptian lawyers are suing Israeli
Prime Minister Netanyahu for his part in the recent desecration of
Islamic and Christian symbols by Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
The trio, two Muslims and a Christian, have filed lawsuits
against Netanyahu, holding him responsible for drawings that
insult the Prophet Mohamed and the Virgin Mary, the Al Ahram
weekly reported today.
</P>
<P>
They believe the "desecration of Islamic and Christian symbols
is part of a broader policy set by Netanyahu and other hardliners."
</P>
<P>
Even if they win, there is no way the Egyptian courts' ruling
can be enforced in Israel, not to mention that the case is of only
moral value. But it is a legal and peaceful way to express their
hurt feelings, according to the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
Mustafa Ashoub is demanding a compensation of 10 billion
U.S. dollars to be spent on building mosques and churches and
helping the families of Palestinians died in the 1987-1993
Intifada (Popular Uprising).
</P>
<P>
Mamdouh Nakhla is requesting 1 million Egyptian pounds (some
294,000 U.S. dollars) but has not decided how to use it.
</P>
<P>
Violence has been raging across the West Bank since late June
when an Israeli woman put up in Hebron offensive posters depicting
Mohamed as a pig writing the Koran, the Islamic holy book. Only a
couple days later, a picture of Virgin Mary painted with the head
of a cow appeared in an Israeli magazine.
</P>
<P>
The three lawyers base their suits on Article 163 of the
Egyptian Civil Code, which stipulates that anyone who causes harm
to any other must pay compensation.
</P>
<P>
They argue that the acts of desecration have inflicted
"definite harm" to both Muslims and Christians and that they stand
to win.
</P>
<P>
Although it appears certain they cannot get the reparation, at
least it would teach the Israelis a lesson that the Arabs should
not be taken lightly, said Nakhla. 
</P>
</TEXT>
