<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- France will withdraw its 1,400 troops stationed in the Central
African Republic in an overall remoulding of its African strategy.
French Defense Minister Alain Richard will visit Gabon, Chad and
Central African Republic next week to inform the leaders of these
countries about the new African policy of France. France will keep
its 550 soldiers in Gabon and 550 others in Chad.
</P>
<P>
-- Some Canadian World War II veterans, most of them
French-speaking but firm federalists, clashed with Quebec
separatists on Wednesday in Quebec during an inauguration ceremony
of a statue of Charles de Gaulle. The ceremony was organized by the
separatists on the 30th anniversary of the visit by the late French
president to Quebec, during which de Gaulle shouted ``Vive le Quebec
libre!'' at the balcony of the city hall of Montreal.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Tens of thousands of paperless immigrants are queuing at
prefectural offices across France to apply for regularization of
their residence status, as the Socialist government has set November
1 as the final date to re-examine residence situation of paperless
immigrants. Meanwhile, the government is continuing to implement the
policy of expelling illegal immigrants which was adopted by the
former government.
</P>
<P>
-- In the trans-Atlantic arms-wrestling for whether to open or
not U.S. air market, Europe held out well as the Boeing Co. agreed
to scrap its 20-year exclusive contracts on plane sales with three
U.S. air companies in exchange for European agreement to its merger
with the McDonnell Douglas Corp.. France remained the most reluctant
to accept the deal, and the Airbus Consortium regretted the
``somewhat arrogant attitude'' of Americans during the negotiations.
</P>
