<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 09:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Right-Wing Group Founded in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Some Israeli extremists have
founded a new right-wing organization called Mahane Yisrael
(Israel Camp), The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The organization's aim is to "destroy myths and restore
honesty in Israeli society", according to founders of the
organization, whose establishment was declared Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Leading extremist Avigdor Eskin, who was among the founders,
said that one of the myths he planned to attack was that of
"Rabin, the holy one," referring to the former Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Rabin who was murdered on November 4, 1995 by an
extremist Jew.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that Rabin was not at all clear-handed during his
highly decorated career, and he called for a retrial of Rabin's
murder Yigal Amir, who is now serving life sentence in prison.
</P>
<P>
Jewish extremism has gained increasing ground among Israeli
society in recent years, especially since the previous Labor
government led by Rabin began the peace process with the
Palestinians and Arab countries based on the principle of
"land-for-peace."
</P>
<P>
The extremist campaign against relinquishing the land of
Greater Israel culminated in the murder of Rabin, who was
apparently the victim of the extremist right-wing incitement
against the peacemaker. Amir claimed he murdered Rabin in order
to kill the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The latest example of Jewish extremism was the pasting of an
anti-Islamic leaflet in late June in the West Bank city Hebron,
which depicted the Islamic prophet Mohammed as a pig.
</P>
<P>
The leaflets were pasted in Palestinian store fronts in Hebron
by Tatiana Susskind, an extremist Jewish woman from Jerusalem
who is associated with the outlawed rightist Kach Movement.
</P>
<P>
The offensive leaflets triggered a new round of violence
between Palestinians and Israeli soldiers, leading to hundreds
wounded and fueling the already tense situation caused by the
stalemate in the peace process since Israel broke ground
for a new Jewish settlement in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
