<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Botswana Diamond Giant Expects More Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Botswana's diamond mining
company Debswana expects to continue improving its profit in the
years ahead, largely as a result of its expansion project at the
Orapa mine, said the company's annual report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The Orapa mine, expected to be completed by 2000, will double
its production from six million carats to 12 million by the
beginning of the next century, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Debswana's 1996/97 profit, announced earlier this year, surged
from three billion Pula (866 million U.S. dollars) to a record
5.2 billion Pula (1.5 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The diamond industry has been Botswana's economic backbone
since the early 1970s, contributing to one third of the GDP --
and its latest performance was the best to date.
</P>
<P>
The good performance was widely attributed to the continuing
strengthening of the U.S. dollar against the Botswana currency,
the Pula, and to the increase in carats produced and sold and
higher prices paid per carat sold, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The review also said the higher profits realized during the
past year were due to increased diamond production which resulted
from the impact being felt from the introduction of additional
plant treatment capacity at Jwaneng mine.
</P>
<P>
Jwaneng is 201 kilometers Southwest of Gaborone, the capital of
Botswana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
