<HEADLINE> S. Africa's De Beers Steps Up Diamond Prospecting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's diamond giant
De Beers is making efforts to prospect diamond mine in
northeastern Angola, a company official said early this week.
</P>
<P>
De Beers had surveyed an area of 4,000 square kilometers in
the provinces of Lunda Norte and Lunda Sul last year, and hoped
to look at a larger area this year, said the official who asked
not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
"We are not ready to start drilling yet, but are locating
possible targets from our aerial surveys," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government awarded De Beers the rights last year
to prospect an area of about 20,000 square kilometers in the
northeast.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, De Beers signed an agreement with its Angolan
counterpart Endiama to build a 30-million U.S. Dollar sorting
house in Luanda for Angolan diamond production.
</P>
<P>
Angola, believe to have the third most valuable diamond mining
resources in the world, produces an estimated two million carats
of diamonds each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
