<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction of First Power Station on Hongshui River in Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The first generating unit at the
Tianshengqiao Hydro-Electric Power Station is scheduled to go on
line in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The station is the first of the 10 lock-and-dam hydro-electric
power stations scheduled for construction on the Hongshui River,
which flows from the Yunnan-Guizhou Plateau in southwest China
through the northwestern part of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
The head engineer said the station's dam will rise 178 meters
in height, and the reservoir will have a holding capacity of 10.2
billion cubic meters of water.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Ministry of Power Industry, Guangdong and Guizhou
provinces, and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region are jointly
financing the project which will be completed at an estimated cost
of 8.7 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
When completed, the station's four generators will have a total
generating capacity of 1.2 million kw and will generate 5.2
billion kwh of electricity.
</P>
<P>
According to the engineer, the 115-meter completed section of
the dam has the capacity to combat major flooding expected to
occur only once in 300 years. He also noted the reservoir will
begin storing this year's flood waters.
</P>
<P>
The first and second lock-and-dam stations are expected to be
completed by the year 2000, and they will have a combined
generating capacity of 2.52 million kw, costing about 20 billion
yuan, including 63.4 billion Japanese yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
