<HEADLINE> Nigerian Women Protest Massive Sack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 24 (Xinhua) -- About 5,000 women yesterday took to
the street in Kaduna City in northern Nigeria, to protest the
massive sack of their husbands by the Kaduna State government.
</P>
<P>
The protesters delivered a letter to the Nigerian head of
state, General Sani Abacha, through the General Officer
Commanding the First Mechanized Infantry Division, Major General
Abdullahi Mukhtar.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, the letter appeals to General
Abacha over the plight of the sacked workers and their entire
families as a result of the "draconian and high-handedness" of
the state administrator, Lieutenant Colonel Hameed Ali.
</P>
<P>
The massive sack has led to the total closure of all public
schools which has forced their children to stay home. Hospitals
have also closed while patients are dying daily, the women said
in the letter.
</P>
<P>
About 34,000 civil servants in the Kaduna State went on strike
on June 16, demanding the payment of increased salaries and
allowances promised by the government in 1995.
</P>
<P>
As the strike continued, the state administrator ordered the
dismissal of all striking workers in early July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
