<HEADLINE> hke072431 - Philippine Rebels Firm on Peace-talk Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Muslim rebels would not
give up the conditions it set earlier for resuming peace
negotiations with the government despite the signing of a general
ceasefire agreement last week, a rebel leader said today.
</P>
<P>
Al Haj Murad, vice-chairman of the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF), was quoted by the Philippine News Agency as saying
that the MILF has not changed its position on the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Murad said that the MILF-government talks last Friday was not a
negotiation but rather an "exploratory" meeting which eventually
led to the signing of a general truce covering the entire
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
He said many MILF members were surprised on the signing of the
agreement because they did not expect it.
</P>
<P>
But Murad said the MILF was not pressured to sign the agreement
and the MILF's position was not compromised in the truce.
</P>
<P>
The MILF has set four conditions for restarting the stalled
peace talks with the government, including the return of displaced
residents to their respective villages and the pull-out of
government troops from the MILF-controlled territories.
</P>
<P>
The MILF frozen the peace talks with the government after its
second biggest camp in central Mindanao was overrun by the
military late last month.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the government began low-level peace talks this
January, but the on-and-off talks have so far failed to achieve
any significant progress.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the larger Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF) which forged a peace deal with the
government last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
