<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists on U.S., Africa Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Political scientists from Africa
and the U.S. met here on Wednesday for a forum aimed at coming up
with a blueprint that will guide relations between the continent
and the U.S. beyond the year 2000, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The four-hour colloquium, sponsored by the African Association
of Political Science (AAPS) and the U.S.-based National Summit on
Africa (NSA) was held on the sidelines of the fourth
African-African American summit which began on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Attended by about 100 delegates, the forum examined ways to
build a strong, cooperative and mutually beneficial relationship
to advance the African agenda of sustainable development, human
rights, democracy, peace and security.
</P>
<P>
NSA Executive Director Macarthur Deshazer told participants
that the summit would mobilize people in the U.S. through a
vibrant policy dialogue which would lead to a new agenda for
U.S./Africa relations.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the NSA' Africa policy initiative, Deshazer said
while this would build upon past efforts to raise awareness on
Africa, it would completely revamp public discourse on U.S.
interaction with Africa.
</P>
<P>
Nzongola-Ntalala, a professor of African studies at the Howard
University in the U.S., said with greater economic self-reliance
and integration and through a mutually beneficial cooperation
with the U.S. and other developed economies, Africans should be
able to improve their lot and thus shape their own political and
economic destiny.
</P>
<P>
Dani Nabudere, a Ugandan academic, urged the U.S. and other
developed countries to help in strengthening rural communities in
Africa as a way of fighting under-development and promoting
socio-economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
