<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Seizes More Fake Bank notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The face value of fake bank notes
of the Thai currency seized last year was as much as 11.28 million
baht (451,000 US dollars), a 656 percent increase over 1995, a
Thai central bank official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
For the first six months of this year, about 13,700 fake notes,
face-valued at 8.7 million baht (341,000 US dollars), were seized,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
Fake notes mostly come from near the border, where they were
traded underground, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Fake notes are often used in the drug trade, or by unscrupulous
employers to pay illegal immigrant workers.
</P>
<P>
The central bank is calling for registration of imported color
photocopying machines for tracing the source of counterfeited bank
notes and for amending laws on penalizing counterfeiting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
