<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya, Ethiopia Promise to Maintain Border Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Kenya and
Ethiopia are committed to maintaining peace, security, law and
order along their common border, the East African Standard paper
today quoted a Kenyan minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return from Addis Ababa yesterday, Foreign Minister
Kalonzo Musyoka noted that the two governments would jointly
fight illicit trade in firearms, narcotics and drug trafficking
along their borders.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan minister, who attended the 31st Kenya/Ethiopia
Joint Ministerial Consultative Committee meeting, pointed out
that the Ethiopian government would hand over hundreds of cattle
and other property stolen from Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
After the hand-over on August 4, he said, the Kenyan
government will seek full compensation for all its nationals
killed in the Marsabit raids taking place last March.
</P>
<P>
During the raids, more than 2,000 armed Ethiopians entered
Marsabit district of Kenya, killing more than 80 people including
17 policemen and stealing hundreds of cattle between March 23 and
25.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting held in Addis Ababa, Musyoka said that both
governments affirmed their commitments to enhance the
relationship between the two neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
