<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Halts Controversial Official Residence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has ordered the suspension of work on a luxury
official residential complex for the head of state, a government
spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Media Minister Mangala Samaraweera told a news briefing that
the president, now on a private visit abroad, called Wednesday
night to order the halt of the work at Sri Jayawardhanapura Kotte.
</P>
<P>
Her order follows criticism and protests against establishing
the complex at a cost of 125 million rupees (about 2.12 million
U.S. dollars) on a 50-acre block of land which would displace over
50 families residing in the area.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to shift the official residence of the head of
state to a location outside Colombo was aimed at reducing the
economic disruption and inconvenience caused by the closure of
roads and other interruptions necessitated by the maintenance of
high security areas in Colombo, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was part of a scheme of the previous government to
establish Colombo as the commercial capital and Sri
Jayawardhanapura Kotte as the administrative capital, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the president had decided not to go ahead with
the construction of the official residential complex until she
returns from abroad.  
</P>
