<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Ophthalmic Treatment in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- An elderly Shanghai man who
had suffered from xerophthalmia for 20 years recently regained
his vision following the successful transplantation of an
"artificial tear duct".
</P>
<P>
"Xerophthalmia" is a type of inflammation caused by serious
trachoma, chemical burns, drug allergies and various other
illnesses. Difficulty in secreting tears eventually causes
either partial or total blindness.
</P>
<P>
The new device represents the culmination of years clinical
research conducted by Professor Zheng Yiren from Shanghai Railway
Central Hospital, a subsidiary unit of Shanghai Railway University.
</P>
<P>
The transplantation procedure requires only 30 minutes, and
the absence of antigen reactions enables patients to regain their
vision within one week.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the new method, which is much more effective than
traditional treatments, will benefit thousands of people suffering
from xerophthalmia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0193 </DOCNO>
