<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 07:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waste Piles up in Beirut, So Does An Enviro-Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Travelers entering Beirut from
the airport have to tolerate stinking smells from now on as the
Lebanese government failed to allot a piece of land to dump
garbage piling up in the capital's suburbs at an average of 600
tonnes a day.
</P>
<P>
Hopes for a quick solution to the waste problem were dashed
when the cabinet, in a regular meeting Wednesday night, did not
find a new dump to replace an old one in the north suburb and
another in the south suburb, which were forced to be closed
following protests of local residents.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and Environment Minister Akram
Chuhayyeb agreed to keep searching for substitutes for both Bourj
Hammoud dump, which was shut down last Saturday, and the Amrousieh
sorting plant and incinerator, which was crippled by arsonists
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
This was announced only hours after Chuhayyeb, emerging from a
meeting with House Speaker Nabih Berri, promised that the
five-day-old problem would be solved in the cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
Beirut's Daily Star newspaper reported Thursday morning that
the environment minister had sought Berri's help to bring the
southern suburbs' residents to agree to the opening of at least
the sorting plant in Amrousieh.
</P>
<P>
However, Chuhayyeb was surprised to hear Berri voicing full
backing to the residents, who are mainly his supporters. The
development added political connotations to the already complex
problem, the only English daily in Lebanon noted.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is not that garbage is piling up in the south and
north suburbs. The main problem we are facing is where to take
that garbage and how to get rid of it in an environmentally
acceptable way," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his ministry was utterly opposed to the idea
of dumping the waste into the sea as part of land reclamation.
</P>
<P>
"Berri is sympathetic to the people's feeling and demands. He
is against having the incinerator near the residential area,"
Chuhayyeb added.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, an environmental organization warned of a
deteriorating situation resulting from garbage which began piling
up in the streets of Beirut's north suburb after the closure of
the Bourj Hammoud dump.
</P>
<P>
The committee for protecting the environment on the coast
called on the government to put into an overall plan for
protecting the environment against pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
