<HEADLINE> Palestinian Negotiator Describes Netanyayu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 24 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
has brushed off Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's call for
immediate talks on staging the final-status talks, reported the
pro-government newspaper, The Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Asfour, senior member of the Palestinian Negotiating
team, told reporters Wednesday night that Netanyahu's proposal is
nothing, but a "trick," designed to enable Israel to retain
the areas occupied 30 years ago in the Six Day War.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the Palestinians still insist in adhering
to the Oslo agreement, under which the Palestinians will
eventually get back more than 90 percent of the occupied
territories in the West Bank. But, according to leaked details
of Netanyahu's favorite "Alon Plus Plan," Israel would only
hand over some 40 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy's upbeat
evaluation of the peace process after meeting Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat in Brussels Tuesday, the Palestinian
negotiator expressed doubt about Levy's sincerity in promising to
reconvene the nine committees and resolve such outstanding issues
as prisoner release, safe passage between the West Bank and
Gaza Strip, and the Palestinian air port and sea port.
</P>
<P>
"Israeli ministers while in international capitals say they are
with the agreement and want to implement it," Asfour said.
"But here they say they are against the agreement and this
is why I doubt what Levy said."
</P>
<P>
Arafat also refuted Levy's remarks, saying: "Nothing was
achieved (with Levy) yesterday." But Levy said: "We have every
reason to be optimistic. We have taken a step forward."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader told reporters in Brussels Wednesday
that "I am looking to achieve something concrete. We are not
asking for the moon."
</P>
<P>
Asfour declared: "There is no room for anything as long
as the land is being confiscated and the file of settlement
activity in the West Bank and Gaza is open." 
</P>
