<HEADLINE> Kenya Resumes Oil Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has signed
two production-sharing contracts with a Canadian company to
resume tapping oil in the country, "Kenya Times" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the three-year contracts, the Canadian company Tornado
Resources expects to spend more than 35 million U.S. Dollars in
exploration covering 42,888 square kilometers in Mandera and
Kilifi districts in northeastern and eastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, Kenyan Energy Minister Kirugi
M'Mukindia said yesterday that Kenya currently spent over 30
percent of her foreign exchange earnings on the import of
petroleum and that any commercial oil or gas discovery would
boost the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
Available data indicated that more than one third of Kenya's
surface area had potential for hydro-carbon exploration, noted
the minister, who tried to encourage other companies to invest in
Kenya's oil exploration.
</P>
<P>
Exploration for oil in Kenya had almost ceased since 1992 when
the World Bank credit expired, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has so far drilled 30 oil exploration wells, 80 to 90
percent of which had not yielded commercial oil, disclosed the
minister, urging the Canadian company to drill more wells so as
to enhance their chances of success. 
</P>
</TEXT>
