<HEADLINE> Beijing Turns More Enterprises Into Joint-Stock Ventures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- This Chinese capital has made
considerable progress in turning its state-owned enterprises into
joint-stock ventures so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics show that the number of joint-stock
enterprises in Beijing rose by 20.5 percent in the first half of
this year to 33,380, with the combined registered capital up 13.7
percent on a yearly basis to more than 63.9 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Direct financing for Beijing firms was on a large scale in the
first half of the year. Between January and June five enterprises
issued A shares -- issued at home and restricted to domestic
investors only -- raising funds valued at more than 1.95 billion
yuan. One company issued B shares -- issued in China but reserved
for overseas investors -- pooling funds worth 327 million Hong
Kong dollars. Another firm raised 1.8 billion Hong Kong dollars
through floating shares in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In another case, a number of promising companies formed the
Beijing Holding Corporation, which was listed in Hong Kong,
raising 2.6 billion Hong Kong dollars in total in the first six
months.
</P>
<P>
By the end of May 3,575 companies had been standardized and
re-registered, about 88.1 percent of all firms whose operations
needed to be straightened out.
</P>
<P>
Municipal official Gao Zuozhi said that Beijing will make
greater efforts to accelerate the pace of transforming large and
medium-sized state-owned enterprises into joint-stock firms in the
remaining months of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
