<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Metropolis Improves Disease Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Extensive health care efforts on
the part of Guangzhou, a major city in south China, have led to
considerable declines in the incidence and mortality rates for
infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
Results of a recent survey indicate that incidence rates for
major contagious diseases have dropped to 0.27 percent, with the
mortality rate standing at only 0.003 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
Investigations in the city mirror western studies listing the
four main killers as malignant tumors, respiratory tract and
cerebrovascular diseases, and heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
The eradication of plague and smallpox has enabled the city
government to focus its attention of childhood diseases. The fact
that some 98 percent of the city's children have received
inoculations has led to a 99 percent reduction in the incidence
rate for diseases such as measles, polio and encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
The city has also adopted a series of regulations governing
management of the food industry and pharmaceuticals manufacturing
sector.
</P>
<P>
A 1996 survey showed that the city was home to 56 medical
institutions per 1,000 people. Doctors and nurses currently
promote medical awareness in villages, with related efforts
yielding greatly improved supplies of potable water and improved
public toilet facilities in rural areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
