<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Black Wednesday for Thailand's Finance Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Dealers call Wednesday "Black
Wednesday" for Thailand's finance sector as most economic news in
the country was horrible.
</P>
<P>
The Thai currency Baht sank to its lowest point in history,
32.5 to the U.S. dollar, compared to the reference rate of 30.842
to the dollar given by the Central Bank for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank intervened in the afternoon when the baht had
weakened to 32.4 against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Trading volume was very small all day, with much of the slide
in the Baht attributed to strong demand for dollars in the local
market.
</P>
<P>
The fall in commercial banks' half-year profits has also caused
short-term negative sentiment in the value of the Baht.
</P>
<P>
Local financial observers said that the current situation
raised questions on the ability of the Central Bank to control the
Baht's slide and whether the government should borrow overseas
funds to supplement foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
With the Baht depreciating by 2-3 percent per day and no signal
indicating at what level the exchange rates might stabilize, the
observers feared that the situation might get out of control.
</P>
<P>
At the stock market, continuing pessimism about the economy
sent the Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) index plunging by 28.50
points, or 4.32 percent, to close at 631.28 points on Wednesday,
hitting hard the banking, finance and communication sectors
especially.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that there were two main factors affecting the
market. The first, it is concerned that the Baht might fall to 40
against the U.S. dollar. The second, the Thai Farmers' Bank, the
third largest bank in the country, raised its minimum lending rate
(MLR) by 100 basis points to 13.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, Somprasong Land P.L.C., a leading Bangkok
property developer, was declared formally in default of 80 million
dollars in convertible bonds, becoming the first Thai company to
default on its foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
The formal default came after Somprasong missed its scheduled
interest payment of 3.1 million U.S. dollars on the debt on
February 5.
</P>
<P>
Along with scores of other developers, Somprasong became a
victim of a three-year slump in the Bangkok property market caused
by overbuilding, high interest rates and an economic slowdown in
the country beginning last year.
</P>
<P>
The frenetic construction boom beginning in the mid-1980s has
transformed the city's skyline and also left much office space and
many high-rise condominiums unoccupied.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the banks were saddled with hundreds of billions
of Baht in non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
Since the latter half of last year, Somprasong had been
involved in fraud scandal and Prasong Panichapakdee, founder of
the company, surrendered to police on fraud allegations against
him.
</P>
<P>
Somprasong shares, which traded at as high as 300 Baht in late
1993, were halted in October at a price of 7.6 Baht.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the bad news indicated the ebbing investor
confidence in the government's policy to revamp the ailing
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The biggest problem now is the lack of clear policies by the
government in dealing with exchange rate, interest rates and
two-tier money market, according to Chatchai Parasuk, first vice
president for national finance and securities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Bank to be Split into Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The National Bank of
Commerce (NBC) of Tanzania will be split into two, with the Trade
and Regional Bank for middle and big customers and a Microfinance
Bank catering for rural and urban small customers.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued here on Wednesday by the State House of
Tanzania said the decision was reached after a cabinet meeting,
chaired by President Benjamin Mkapa in Dodoma, central Tanzania
this week.
</P>
<P>
The statement said a three-bank structure earlier proposed by
the government, causing a lot of queries and suspicion, was found
to have less efficiency compared with the two-bank structure.
</P>
<P>
The two-bank structure was formulated by combining trade and
regional banks to get one Trade and Regional Bank which would
make more profit than running the two banks separately.
</P>
<P>
"Under this structure, expectations to secure loans from
donors will be higher," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement further said the government decided on the
two-bank structure option after considering its diversified
advantages including its ability to hasten economic growth by
using existing NBC branch network.
</P>
<P>
The structure would enable the Microfinance Bank to start
within a short time, using the existing network and also
minimizing the disturbance of shifting customers to appropriate
banks.
</P>
<P>
Under this structure, the Microfinance Bank would allow faster
collection of deposits from new shareholders and providing loans
to small customers more efficiently, the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
