<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Island Province Improves Health Care in Rural Part </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Thanks to improved health care
facilities in the rural regions of southernmost China's Hainan
Province, life expectancy has risen to just over 73 years,
compared with the national average of 70.
</P>
<P>
Another indication of the island province's improved health
care is that the overall incidence of infectious diseases was
brought below the national average in 1996. The figure of 1987,
before the formal establishment of the province, was three times
the national average.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, provincial authorities have invested 118
million yuan in building 146,000 sq m of medical treatment and
health care facilities and training 5,385 medical personnel in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some 72,000 farmers have joined a cooperative
medical service program, in which each participant pays 15 to 60
yuan each year to a medical service fund to cover their medical
expenses.
</P>
<P>
By 1996, a total of 6.05 million farmers, or 95.91 percent of
Hainan's rural population, benefited from a project to improve the
water supply in rural areas. This year, the provincial treasury
will appropriate 800,000 yuan in renovation of toilets in the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
It is reported Hainan plans to build 80 rural hospitals over
the next few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
