<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Wants African Economic Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
envoy to the fourth Africa-African American (AAA) summit Rodney
Slaver has implored African countries to unite in the light of
globalization of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gala at the summit venue in Harare last night,
Slaver said Africa is the land of opportunity which should be
able to lead the world into forging a global economy that
represents interests of all people.
</P>
<P>
He said, "President Clinton is pleased that we are having to
meet here with the spirit that represents and unites Americans
with the rest of Africa."
</P>
<P>
"It should be realized that Africa is a true land of
opportunity and should be our trading partner to lead the world
into this global economy that is emerging in the 21st century,"
said Slaver who is Transportation Secretary of the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Commercial diplomacy, he said, and true friendship should be
the policy to guide African leaders and their American
counterparts into improving the world's poorest continent.
</P>
<P>
Slaver praised the summit for fighting for the economic
development of the African continent.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, he told Zimbabwean Minister of Transport and
Energy Simon Moyo that the U.S. government is interested and
ready to help in the development of the Southern African
Development Community's (SADC) transport sector.
</P>
<P>
He added his government is ready to work closely with the
SADC. 
</P>
