<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Introduces Land Planning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEHEI, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Anhui Province, east China, has
adopted measures to increase farmland by rearranging the layout of
villages and townships.
</P>
<P>
According to the provincial construction department, land
planning introduced to 78 percent of the province's villages and
townships will increase farmland acreage by some 60,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
The random distribution of housing in rural areas not only
occupied vast tracts of land, but also hinders efforts to improve
local infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Xiaogang Village, Fengyang County, straightened roads and was
able to reclaim 0.6 ha of the former four ha land coverage.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,320 of 2,000 villages in the county have introduced
reclamation programs, with related programs expected to increase
cultivatable land by as much as 860 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Xiaozhangzhuang, Yingshang County, has consolidated 11 scattered
villages into four new districts.
</P>
<P>
China is currently waging a nationwide campaign to halt the use
of cultivatable land for commercial purposes in order maximize the
use of limited land resources to feed its large population.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
