<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir Stresses Importance of Economic Prosperity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING Jaya, Malaysia, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad today described economic strength as
"all-important," saying stability, economic strength and the
willingness to stay together will be the ASEAN's ultimate defense.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the 30 ASEAN Ministerial
Meeting here, Mahathir called for dedication to economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"The threat faced by nations is economic sanctions to
impoverish the people and to stir internal strife," Mahathir said.
"We should therefore concentrate on economic development and the
well-being of our people."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that with the admission of Laos and Myanmar as
the ASEAN's new members, Southeast Asian countries can cooperate
and help each other to prosper economically. "That way we will
become internally stable and less susceptible to the kind of
outside pressures our detractors like to apply."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to some Western countries' opposition to the
ASEAN's inclusion in its membership of Myanmar, which was accused
of human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said, "Economic prosperity is really the answer to our
security problems because with prosperity the ASEAN will be taken
seriously and its views respected." "Prosperity is essential for
the avoidance of internal conflict."
</P>
<P>
He blamed the current currency crisis in some Southeast Asian
countries on "a well-planned effort to undermine the economies of
all the ASEAN countries by destabilizing their currencies."
</P>
<P>
"Our economic fundamentals are good yet anyone with a few
billion dollars can destroy all the progress that we have made,"
he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also accused giant companies in the world of
swallowing up chunks of the business in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
"They monopolize the services sector through their huge
shipping, airlines, insurance companies and banks. The media,
print and electronic, are now controlled by them throughout the
world," he charged. "We are denied press freedom by the many
people who trumpet press freedom. Only bad news about us is
published, the good news is often buried in their archives."
</P>
<P>
He called on the countries in Southeast Asia to stand together,
stressing that alone, none of the Southeast Asian countries will
be able to protect itself. "But nine ASEAN countries with half a
billion people may be able to do something to help ourselves."
</P>
</TEXT>
