<HEADLINE> Hungary Opens Consulate in Northwest Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 23 (Xinhua) -- In another sign of improving
relations between Hungary and Romania, a Hungarian consulate
general officially opened today in Cluj-Napoca in northwest
Romania.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference after the opening ceremony,
foreign ministers from both countries expressed satisfaction over
the development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Foreign Minister Adrian Severin described the good
relations between Hungary and Romania as a pillar of long-term
security and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
His Hungarian counterpart, Kovacs Laszlo, said the era of
mistrust and antagonism between the two nations had already ended.
</P>
<P>
Kovacs said that the new road taken by the two countries is not
only in the interests of the minorities living in each other's
countries, but also in the interests of European security.
</P>
<P>
The development of relations between Hungary and Romania over
the past seven to eight months has been faster than over the past
seven years, he added.
</P>
<P>
Romania and Hungary signed a historic friendship treaty in
September last year, paving way for reconciliation after a long
standing rift between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral relations were strained over a 1920 territorial
settlement which cut off some three fifths of Hungary's territory,
including Transylvania which was transferred to Romania.
</P>
<P>
The Cluj-Napoca area in Romania, which has a dominant ethnic
Hungarian population, has long been a thorn in the side of
relations between the two countries. In the early 1990s, ethnic
Hungarians launched a violent campaign to get the area returned
to Hungary.
</P>
<P>
The former Hungarian consulate in the area was closed on
charges of anti-Romanian activities in 1988 after operating for
nine years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
