<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Launches Campaign against Tuberculosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Nepal has launched a program to
prevent and control tuberculosis (TB), which is affecting a
growing number of the country's population, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the program entitled "Tuberculosis and AIDS" on
Wednesday, Minister of State for Health Bharat Kumar Pradhan said
the government is determined to check the growing number of TB
patients in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, organized by the Nepal Anti-tuberculosis
Association, the traditional "Direct Observation Treatment" short
course (DOTs) will be maintained and door to door health services
will be provided, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that 45,000 Nepalese are being
affected by TB every year and 16,500 of them die.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of the TB patients in Nepal live in urban
areas, while the rest live in the mountainous regions.
</P>
<P>
And 70 percent of the HIV-AIDS patients have been found
suffering from TB as well, a program report said.
</P>
<P>
The HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, weakens the immunity power
of the patients and cause them die of TB soon, it said.
</P>
<P>
Director of the National TB Center Dirgha Singh Bam disclosed
at the program that modern treatment centers will be set up in 30
places under the current fiscal year beginning July 15, providing
medical services to 12 percent of the TB patients.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the threat of TB is as it was 50 years ago as a
result of increasing urbanization, poverty and illiteracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
