<HEADLINE> Milosevic Becomes Yugoslav President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Slobodan Milosevic, chairman of
the Socialist Party of Serbia, was sworn in today as the president
of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic, twice the president of the Republic of Serbia, was
elected on July 15 by the People's Assembly, or parliament, of the
reduced Yugoslavia, with votes of 88 against 29.
</P>
<P>
In his inauguration speech today, Milosevic said Yugoslavia is
facing the difficult work of carrying out programs for physical
and spiritual renewal and the social transformation.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to maintain the equal and free development of Serbia
and Montenegro, the two republics of Yugoslavia, and to safeguard
the peace and prosperity of all citizens of the country.
</P>
<P>
He urged all Yugoslavs to show patriotism, saying a peaceful,
free and independent Yugoslavia is in the interest of everything.
</P>
<P>
The new president also accused the sanctions by the
international community of interfering in Yugoslavia, and of
seriously destabilizing the nation's society and economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
