<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Opposes U.S. Proposals for U.N. Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Italian leaders today opposed
United States' proposals to reform the United Nations Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
"Italy opposes any increase in the number of permanent council
members, fearing that it will make a small number of members in
the Security Council gain more privileges instead of reflecting
the current world situation," said a statement released after
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi met U.S. ambassador to the
U.N. Bill Richardson today.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the U.S. proposed enlarging the 15-member Security
Council, the U.N. body concerned with international peace and
security, by adding five permanent members -- Germany, Japan and
three developing countries -- to the existing five permanent
members and 10 non-permanent members.
</P>
<P>
But Italy has suggested the U.N. set up between 10 and 20
semi-permanent seats which would be shared on a rotating basis by
some 30 countries.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini echoed Prodi's comments
after meeting Richardson.
</P>
<P>
Dini, in a second statement, said that Italy believes
U.S. proposals for Security Council reform are not only
incompatible with democracy, but also helpful to a few countries
in winning privileges and harmful to Italy. He said the reforms
are a source of separation and confrontation.
</P>
<P>
"Reforms of the top body of the U.N. should strictly comply with
democratic principles with wide representation," it added.
</P>
<P>
But both Italy and United States have previously agreed that
the U.N. must be more efficient to meet the demands of a new world
reality.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that proposals made by
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan last week to streamline
organizations, improve efficiency and cut spending at the U.N. are
useful.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said today's meetings signaled that the U.S. and Italy
are far apart on U.N. reform proposals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
