<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Australia Agree to Expand Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- China and Australia have agreed
to expand their rapidly-developing trade and investment
cooperation during a two-day "constructive" meeting held here, a
senior Chinese official told Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting attended by senior Chinese and Australian economic
officials, focused on further cooperation in wool industry,
investment promotion and market access issues.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and Australian officials attending the meetings
included Shi Guangsheng, vice minister of the Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation, and Philip Flood, secretary of the
Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT), or executive
deputy minister.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, or the Intersessional Meeting of the Ninth
Joint Ministerial Economic Commission (JMEC) between China and
Australia, the two sides also discussed the issue of expanding
JMEC, the Chinese vice minister said.
</P>
<P>
There is a great potential for rapid expansion of bilateral
trade and investment cooperation and the two economies are
complementary to each other, the vice minister said.
</P>
<P>
Australia, China's biggest overseas investment destination, is
expected to absorb more Chinese investment in the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
China also welcome Australia's investment in such fields as
agriculture, transportation, energy, high-technology and
export-oriented business. The actual Australian investment in
China totaled one billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The JMEC, established in 1986, meets regularly at ministerial
level every two years and at vice-ministerial level every other
year. It is an important element in an expanding web of bilateral
consultations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Intersessional Meeting came after the agreement reached
between Chinese Premier Li Peng and Australian Prime Minister John
Howard during Howard's visit to China early this year to
reinvigorate the JMEC process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
