<HEADLINE> Johnson Heads US Team for Athletics Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Olympic double champion Michael
Johnson will spearhead the American squad, together with six other
defending world champions, for the World Athletics Championships
to be started on August 1, the USA Track and Field said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, winner of the men's 200 and 400 meters in Atlanta,
will compete in the 400 meters at the 10-day championships in
Athens. Besides, he also will be a member of the U.S. men's
4x400-meter relay pool.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 world champion at 200 and 400 meters was given a
wild-card entry into the championships by the IAAF, the world
governing body for the sport, after he missed the U.S. trials
because of injury.
</P>
<P>
Other wild cards receivers include world champions Gail Devers,
Gwen Torrence, John Godina.
</P>
<P>
Devers, two-time women's 100-meter hurdles gold medalist, will
anchor the women's 4x100-meter relay team and Torrence will defend
her women's 100-meter title.
</P>
<P>
Godina, world champion in men's shot put, will compete in both
shot put and discus.
</P>
<P>
The American team also features new sprint stars Maurice Greene
and Marion Jones as well as 110-meter hurdler Allen Johnson,
400-meter hurdler Derrick Adkins and women's 400-meter hurdler Kin
Batten. The latter three won gold medals at the 1995 world
championships in Gothenburg, Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
