<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment in Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- According to Michael Portoh,
chief-executive of Bayer (China) Limited, "Those who want to
occupy the Chinese market must first enter the capital city of
Beijing."
</P>
<P>
The output value of a joint pharmaceutical venture set up by
this German multinational giant and local investor is expected to
exceed 100 million yuan (about 12 million US dollars) at year
end. Following that success, the German company has invested 1.25
million yuan in another joint venture in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Like Bayer, more overseas investors are viewing Beijing as an
important place to put their investment.
</P>
<P>
According to municipal government statistics, 279
multinationals and big foreign companies have put a total of 4.6
billion yuan in some 370 projects in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors have been impressed by the Chinese capital,
which has many hi-tech companies, research and educational
institutions, skilled professionals, and a potential market.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Mayor Lu Yucheng, who is in charge of foreign
investment, told Xinhua that Beijing is improving its
infrastructure and laws and regulations to prepare for a new round
of overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Lu says that Beijing is an economic and financial center and is
one of the cities listed by the central government for opening
their financial sector to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
It has also taken substantial steps to simplify procedures for
foreign investment and to crack down on illegal charges placed on
these firms.
</P>
<P>
And, the city's efforts to lure foreign investment have paid
off. Eighty international giants have moved their regional
headquarters to the city, while 12 foreign banks have opened
branches here.
</P>
<P>
As of May of this year, investors from 94 foreign countries and
regions have founded 12,939 solely foreign-funded firms and
Sino-foreign joint ventures with a total investment of 20.16
billion US dollars, according to official figures. Ninety percent
of these are in electronics, service, and food industries.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say that foreign investors have had good
returns from their investment in Beijing, and, as a result, have
invested more in Beijing. In 1996 alone, foreign-funded firms here
added over 600 million US dollars in investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
