<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright on U.S. Goals at Coming ASEAN Regional Forum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES Angeles, July 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright said here today the United States
supports new multilateral security dialogue forums such as the
ASEAN Regional Forum.
</P>
<P>
She said the Forum's growing importance reflects the fact that
security in the Asia-Pacific "is not a zero-sum game."
</P>
<P>
Albright, on her way to Malaysia to attend the annual meeting
of the ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) Regional
Forum, was addressing a luncheon meeting of 1,000 people hosted by
the Los Angeles World Affairs Council and the Pacific Council.
</P>
<P>
Each Forum participant, including not only ASEAN members but
also the U.S., China, Russia, Japan, the European Union, India and
South Korea, she said, "has an interest in stability, in seeing
disputes resolved peacefully and in avoiding misunderstandings
that could lead to armed conflicts."
</P>
<P>
The United States has placed priority "on improving ties
throughout the Asia-Pacific", Albright said ahead of her third
trip to Asia in six months as Secretary of State. She said she
would discuss "a full range of issues" with her Asian counterparts
when she visits Kuala Lumpur and later Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about China, Albright said she is to
discuss a wide range of issues with Chinese Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen in Kuala Lumpur. "What is very important to us is
developing a strategic relationship with China," she said, adding
that China will play a crucial role in many of the issues of the
21st century the United States cares about.
</P>
<P>
Turning to economic and trade issues, Albright said the United
States would encourage ASEAN to continue opening up markets and
liberalizing trade, and pressing for better enforcement of
intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
"I will also ask ASEAN to help reach a worldwide agreement this
year to liberalize financial services," she said.
</P>
<P>
Discussing the wide-spread warning of a future conflict between
East and West in terms of civilizations, cultures and values,
Albright said distinctions of national identity and culture should
not melt away in the context of globalization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
