<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China to Spend More on Building Expressways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province will
put up more than 19 billion yuan before 2010 on building 1,240 km
of new expressways that will link nine prefectures and cities.
</P>
<P>
East China is one of China's economically-developed areas, but
Fujian has lagged behind owing to inconvenient transport.
</P>
<P>
The new expressways will be built in two phases, between 2000
and 2010. One, with a length of 700 km, will go from Fenshuiguan
of Fuding on the Fujian and Zhejiang borders and ending at
Fenshuiguan of Zhao'an on the Fujian-Guangdong border.
</P>
<P>
The other two will be the 420-km Fujian section of the
Beijing-Fuzhou Expressway and 120-km Zhangzhou-Longyan Expressway.
</P>
<P>
The province will also spend nine billion yuan on finishing the
Quanzhou-Xiamen, Xiamen-Zhangzhou, and Fuzhou-Quanzhou expressways
before the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, workers have completed 92 percent
of the World Bank-financed Quanzhou-Xiamen Expressway.
</P>
<P>
The entire project will be finished in September and put into
trial use later this year. The Xiamen-Zhangzhou Expressway will be
finished simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
Workers have been hard at work on the Fuzhou-Quanzhou
Expressway which is expected to be finished in September of 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the past several years, the province has built 3,768 km of
roads and has formed a transport network consisting of trunk
highways, as part of its "highway first" program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Brings Market Mechanism Into Water-Supply Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Nowadays in some eastern cities
many local residents are relying on mineral water bought in the
market, owing to shortages of tap water in the area.
</P>
<P>
"The introduction of the market system could turn water
resources into a commodity and reservoirs into enterprises," said
Zhang Mengjin, director of the Water Resources Department of
Zhejiang Province in east China.
</P>
<P>
Water supply has long been seen as a matter of social welfare
in China, with the government responsible for building reservoirs,
water plants and other water-supply facilities.
</P>
<P>
In recent years Zhejiang has introduced a brand-new idea of
making reservoirs independent enterprises responsible for their
profits and losses. Niu Maosheng, minister of water resources, has
highly appraised the idea.
</P>
<P>
To bring water use under the law of the market, the central
government has put the prices of water supplied by state-run
reservoirs under the national commodity pricing management system.
</P>
<P>
Water prices will be set by the Ministry of Water Resources
with due consideration to the prices of industrial, agricultural
and residential commodities.
</P>
<P>
The State Council has also drawn up plans to raise funds for
national and local water conservancy projects in an effort to
accelerate water conservancy construction.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, the central government plans to turn
both water conservancy firms and hydropower suppliers into public
companies, and some of them will be listed on the stock markets.
</P>
<P>
These efforts are expected to help solve the problem of wasted
water and the lack of investment in water conservancy projects.
</P>
<P>
At present, among more than 32,000 water-supply enterprises in
China, 900 are share-holding ones. More than 300 billion
yuan-worth of state-owned assets and a total of one million people
are involved in the sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mugabe Reshuffles Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 24 (Xinhua) -- President Robert Mugabe has
reshuffled his cabinet, merging eight ministries into four,
creating a new one, which will result in administrative savings
in today's budget, an official statement said today.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the Office of the President and Cabinet said
the Ministry of Local Government, Rural and Urban Development was
merged with that of public construction and national housing to
become the Ministry of Local Government and National Housing
during the reshuffle on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
John Nkomo heads the enlarged ministry with Tony Gara as his
deputy.
</P>
<P>
Education, Sports and Culture Ministry, headed by Gabriel
Machinga and Kembo Mohadi as his new deputy, replaced the
Ministry of Education and the Ministry of Sports, Recreation and
Culture.
</P>
<P>
Simon Moyo, formerly minister of transport and energy, moved
to the expanded Ministry of Mines, Environment and Tourism.
Edward Chinndori-Chininga is his deputy.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Lands and Water Resources was merged with the
Ministry of Agriculture to become the Ministry of Lands and
Agriculture under Kumbirai Kangai. Olivia Muchena is his deputy.
</P>
<P>
"A new Ministry of Rural Resources and Water Development has
been formed and will be headed by Joyce Mujure, with Cain Mathema
as her deputy," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
