<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Ministerial Meeting Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING, Jaya, Malaysia, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad opened the 30th Ministerial Meeting of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) here this
morning with a speech defending the group's admission of Laos and
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, in his speech at the opening ceremony, criticized
some people for exerting pressure on the ASEAN over its membership
expansion.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Laos and Myanmar were formally admitted into the
ASEAN at a ceremony in Petaling, Java of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"The world should welcome the accession to the ASEAN of any
country which qualifies," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is regrettable that there are those who would not see the
obvious. Instead of encouraging the ASEAN to accept all Southeast
Asian countries as soon as possible, the ASEAN has been urged to
pass judgment, deny membership and apply pressure on a potential
candidate so as to force that country to remain poor and therefore
unstable," Mahathir said, without picking out names.
</P>
<P>
When the ASEAN decided to admit Myanmar in May this year, some
Western countries, mainly the United States, expressed their
objection, accusing the country of human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
"The ASEAN must resist and reject such attempts at coercion,"
he said, "No one should assume that only they know the solutions
to all problems."
</P>
<P>
The opening ceremony were attended by ASEAN Secretary-General
Ajit Singh, foreign ministers of the nine ASEAN member countries
-- Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam -- and representatives of Papua
New Guinea and Cambodia, which enjoy observer status in the
regional grouping.
</P>
<P>
Laos and Myanmar are participating in the ASEAN Ministerial
Meeting for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN had agreed to admit Cambodia simultaneously with Laos
and Myanmar in May, but it decided earlier this month to defer its
entry because of fighting between the forces of Co-Prime Ministers
Norodom Ranariddh and Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN foreign ministers upheld the decision Wednesday after
Cambodian Foreign Minister Ung Huot, who is here for the
ministerial meeting, said his country still wants to join the
organization and welcomes its effort to end the fighting in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
