<HEADLINE> New Rebel Group Surfaces in Nicaragua </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- A new rebel group has surfaced in
northern Nicaragua and declared its objective as to combat what it
called the "savage capitalism" in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Northern Diriangen Front, or the FND in Spanish, delivered
a press release, with a seal that reads "National Command of the
Joint Staffs," to the local newspaper La Tribuna.
</P>
<P>
Its statement came two days after the government claimed
success in demobilizing the 3-80 Northern Front, a rebel group
active in the northern part of this Central American country.
</P>
<P>
The new rebel group said it was taking up arms to fight the
government of President Arnoldo Aleman's policy, which it
described was "the living expression of Somocism."
</P>
<P>
In the release, the FND said it is made up of former members of
army and resistance groups, and its militants include
professionals, farmers, students, mechanics and teachers.
</P>
<P>
The FND attributed the "misery, unemployment, hunger and
extreme poverty" among the Nicaraguan people to the neo-liberal
policy being practiced in the country.
</P>
<P>
Corruption, influence peddling, high taxes, illegal
profiteering, concessions to foreigners and human rights
violations, it alleged, are characteristic of the current system.
</P>
<P>
In view of the poor perspectives for the future, the FND has no
alternative other than protest with arms, said the release.
</P>
<P>
After the peaceful demobilization of the 3-80 Northern Front on
Monday, the Nicaraguan government is trying to get three other
groups to lay down their arms in northern and central Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
The groups, known to have Sandinista leanings, are the Andres
Castro United Front, the Ramon Raudales Northern Front and the
Revolutionary Worker and Peasant Front. 
</P>
</TEXT>
