<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Stepping up Drive to Defend Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine monetary authorities
have stepped up its drive to defend the peso by issuing a new set
of guidelines to banks to curb renewed speculation on the
currency.
</P>
<P>
In a circular published here today, Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson ordered suspending for three months so-called
"non-deliverable forward sales" of the U.S. dollar so as to enable
monetary authorities to strengthen regulations against these
transactions.
</P>
<P>
Singson said that approval by the central bank is needed in all
non-deliverable forward contracts of on-shore banks to sell
dollars to non-residents.
</P>
<P>
"In order to curb undue speculations in the foreign exchange
market, all forward contracts to sell foreign exchange to
non-residents shall be submitted for prior clearance to the
central bank," he said in the circular.
</P>
<P>
In another move, the central bank Wednesday reduced the
overbought dollar limit of banks to 10 percent from 20 percent of
their unimpaired capital, while raising the oversold dollar limit
of banks to 20 percent from the previous 10 percent of their
unimpaired capital.
</P>
<P>
The overbought position is defined as the excess of foreign
exchange assets over liabilities, while the oversold position is
the excess of foreign exchange liabilities over assets.
</P>
<P>
After two weeks of turmoil in the Philippine foreign exchange
market, the peso has become steady. It closed at 28.50 against the
U.S. dollar Wednesday. The currency has been under heavy pressure
of speculation since its 11.5 percent devaluation on July 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
