<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Calls for Better Work in Family Planning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng has noted
that the country's population situation remains serious despite
some achievements last year, and that family planning must be
given due attention every year.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remark March 8 at a forum on family planning and
environmental protection. The full text of his speech was made
public by Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the country's birth rate was nearly 17 per thousand,
and the natural increase rate of the population was a little over
ten per thousand. Both figures were slightly lower than those in
1995.
</P>
<P>
"While affirming the achievements, we should also recognize
that China's population situation remains serious," Li said,
explaining that China now has a huge population, that family
planning is weak in the rural and impoverished areas, and that it
is hard to control population growth among the floating population.
</P>
<P>
"Governments at various levels must become fully aware of the
long-term and arduous nature of population control, and must
unswervingly carry out the basic national policy of family
planning," he said.
</P>
<P>
Family planning should be given due attention every year, so
that the country's population will not exceed 1.3 billion by the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In this sense, the premier pointed out, the effective policies
and methods for family planning formed in the past two decades
should be retained and be improved in the course of practice.
</P>
<P>
The policies and methods include the encouragement of late
marriage and late birth, one child per couple, a responsibility
system for local family planning officials, proper services to
ensure planned births and making people more aware of the
country's population situation.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng stressed that it is hard to carry out family planning
in rural areas. Efforts must be centered on the countryside so
that the target for family planning in the country's Ninth
Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000) can be met.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas family planning should be carried out together
with the development of the rural economy, assisting local farmers
to become rich and establishing civilized and happy families. In
poor areas family planning should be linked to poverty
alleviation, Li said.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Li also put emphasis on the better management of
family planning among the floating population. At present, more
people are moving from the countryside to cities and boom areas,
which benefits economic growth but makes population management
more difficult.
</P>
<P>
With regard to family planning in urban areas, Li noted that
the birth rate is already low there, but related work should not
be relaxed. He also called on local governments to create good
conditions for the education of only children in cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
