<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Central Bank Intervenes to Defend Rupiah </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's central bank has spent
so far this week 700 million U.S. dollars to defend the country's
currency rupiah against speculators, according to bank governor
Soedradjad Djiwandono.
</P>
<P>
Bank Indonesia bought rupiah in the forward market on Monday
and Tuesday, the governor said here Wednesday night. The bank
would intervene again if it is necessary, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The situation could get critical again if speculators carry on
playing with our currency, but the bank will be careful to avoid a
repeat of Monday's sudden 7.1 percent drop," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to make sure this does not wreck our economy," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has 21 billion dollars in reserves, equivalent
to more than five months of imports, Soedradjad said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, speculators targeted the rupiah after forcing a
devaluation of the Thai baht and the Philippine peso earlier in
the month.
</P>
<P>
Soedradjad conceded that the government's 4 percent annual
depreciation target for the rupiah will probably prove untenable
this year, and that a 5 percent depreciation was now more likely.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the rupiah has tumbled 8.7 percent against
the dollar. It was recently traded at 2,575 to the dollar. It hit
a record low of 2,665 rupiah to the dollar on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"President Soeharto has told us to keep the rupiah stable, but
we don't know whether the speculators will stop -- so we have to
be careful and stay on our guard," the governor said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank on July 11 widened the dollar-rupiah
intervention band to 12 percent from 8 percent to avert
speculative attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
