<HEADLINE> Chinese University Students Keen to Learn to Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- The former craze among college
students -- learning how to use a computer -- is being replaced by
learning how to drive before graduation.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing University, in the southwestern part of China, is
offering an elective course in response to strong demand by many
students, who want to get a driver's license before they leave the
university.
</P>
<P>
Students have to pay 2,000 yuan for the course, an amount that
is nearly equal to the total they spend on everything else for the
rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
Most of the students involved want to be more versatile and to
learn more to be better prepared for the future.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Bin, one of the students who took the Chongqing course,
says that he did it because he thought he could find a better job
if he had a driver's license. Most of the students say that they
will have a chance to drive after graduation -- and the course
gives them additional credit.  
</P>
</TEXT>
