<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica Institutionalizes Funding for Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican President Jose Maria
Figueres today approved a constitutional reform bill to allocate 6
percent of the country's gross domestic product (GDP) to education.
</P>
<P>
The universities currently enjoy a financing system that has
been under fire from people in the political and financial
circles, who see the fundings for higher education as excessive.
</P>
<P>
Introduced at a time when there is an increasing tendency to
privatize Costa Rica's higher education institutions, the reform
bill aims to reinforce basic education, including preschooling.
</P>
<P>
The measure stipulates that financing for public education
shall not be less than 6 percent of the GDP, or the country's
total value of annual output of goods and services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Deficit Drops in Czech Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The Czech National Statistics
Bureau said today that the foreign trade deficit in the country
were 9.58 billion korun (2.8 billion U.S. dollars) in June, the
lowest in the past 16 months.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that the exports increased by 31 percent
and imports 17.8 percent, compared with those in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
The drop of the foreign trade deficit helps the increase of
exchange rate between korun, U.S. dollar and deutsche mark.
</P>
<P>
The huge foreign trade deficit in the Czech Republic in the
past few years has been attributed to the decrease of exports and
rise of imports. In 1996, the deficit totalled 161 billion korun
(4.9 billion dollars) and 40.2 billion korun (1.2 billion dollars)
in the first quarter of this year, a 47.8-percent increase over
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit has been one of the major obstacles for the
country's economic development. To improve the situation, the
Czech authorities took a series of measures to encourage exports
and limit imports. Importers must pay 20 percent of import
deposits of their total import volume to the state-designated
banks, but the banks will not pay interest to the import
deposits. The measure has curbed the rapid rise of imports in the
country. Experts estimate that the deficit this year will be much
lower than last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
