<HEADLINE> Judicial Reform in Argentina to be Financed by IDB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The Argentine government and
the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) signed an agreement
today on financing the reform of the country's judicial system.
</P>
<P>
The technical-financial cooperation agreement was signed by
Argentine Justice Minister Raul Granillo Ocampo and IDB
representative Jose Maria Puppo in this capital.
</P>
<P>
It calls for IDB financing for two-month initial work by nine
national and international experts to determine what changes
should be made in Argentina's judicial system.
</P>
<P>
In a step that follows, the IDB, based in Washington D.C., the
United States, will evaluate the disbursement of 10 million U.S.
dollars to carry out the proposals.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, Ocampo said the IDB loan will enable
Argentina to go on with reforms in various areas that are affected
by the judicial system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
