<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Albanian Parliament Opens 1st Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The new People's Assembly of
Albania (parliament) elected on June 29, the 15th in history of
the nation, held its first session here today to establish a
credential committee on parliament members.
</P>
<P>
However, all parliament members of the Democratic Party failed
to attend today's meeting. The new assembly is composed of 155
members, out of which, 105 are Socialists and 27 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
Genc Pollo, secretary-general of the Democratic Party, told the
press today that parliament members from his party will not attend
forthcoming parliamentary meetings which will elect parliament
speaker, president of the state and cabinet, in order to protest
against violence and revenging actions during the general
elections late last month.
</P>
<P>
But, he pointed out, it didn't mean his party boycotted the new
parliament, which was described by international monitors as
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
The parliament is expected to elect Socialist Party Secretary
General Rexhep Mejdani as the president to replace Sali Berisha.
</P>
<P>
Top priorities for the new parliament will be to restore law
and order and to resolve the economic issues resulted from the
collapse of the fraudulent investment schemes earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
A military violence engulfed Albania, killing more than 400
people after a nationwide unrest caused by the collapse of the
fraudulent schemes, in which, hundreds and thousands of Albanian
lost money.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the Balkan country remains precarious with the
gradual withdrawal of the Italian-led 7,000 strong multinational
troops who were deployed in April to secure aid deliveries.
</P>
<P>
All the troops are expected to pull out of the tiny nation
within August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
