<HEADLINE> Ukraine Hopes for Strategic Partnership with Armenia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine hopes to establish a
strategic partnership with Armenia, Ukrainian President Leonid
Kuchma said today at a meeting with his Armenian counterpart Levon
Ter-Petrocyan.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma said there are no political differences between Ukraine
and Armenia, so it is a natural choice for the two countries to
develop a strategic partnership.
</P>
<P>
Ter-Petrocyan, who arrived here yesterday on a two-day visit,
said Armenia pays great attention to promoting relations with
neighboring countries and is ready to undertake military
cooperation with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine and Armenia developed a powerful military industry
during the Soviet era, so there is great potential for military
cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
But both stressed the aim of the military cooperation is to
maintain and enhance peace.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma, whose country has been suffering from a sluggish
economy since independence in 1991, also stressed the importance
of developing economic and trade cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between the two former Soviet republics stood at
29 million U.S. dollars in 1996 and four million dollars in the
first five months of 1997. 
</P>
