<HEADLINE> China Investment Bank To Become Shareholding Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- China Investment Bank (CIB) will
complete its transformation into a shareholding business by the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The bank's directional shift in operations, following two years
of readjustment, will continue being its main task in the latter
half of the year and the bank is scheduled to finish floating
shares by the end of the year, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
CIB, established in 1981, used to relend World Bank loans to
small and medium-sized enterprises in China.
</P>
<P>
The bank, which began its transformation into a commercial bank
in 1994 along with China's "Big Four" State-owned banks, reported
sound capital operations during the first half of the year, says
the English-language newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the bank issued 100 million US dollars
floating rate bonds in Hong Kong, marking its return to the
capital market. 
</P>
