<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Condemns Canada over Ferry Blockade Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate today condemned
Canada for failing to bring a swift end to the blockade of an
American ferry by angry British Columbia fishermen.
</P>
<P>
Senators voted 81-19 to approve a nonbinding resolution
censuring Canada and urging U.S. President Bill Clinton to impose
sanctions against Canada in the event of a recurrence.
</P>
<P>
Canadian fishermen used boats blockaded a U.S. Alaskan ferry at
a Canadian harbor last weekend, protesting fishermen of Alaska
catch to much salmon in the pacific.
</P>
<P>
Canada and the U.S. signed a treaty in 1985 to regulate fishing
activities and divide the amount of fish the two sides can
catch. Canada accused the U.S. of breaching the treaty by
over-fishing.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also announced today that they each will
appoint a prominent citizen who will seek a negotiated settlement
to the salmon dispute.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said the two
prominent citizens will "act as a resource" to stake-holders or
regional fishing representatives who have tried without success to
reach a compromise settlement.
</P>
<P>
"The objective is to move this process quickly enough to make a
positive difference in the 1998 salmon season," Burns said.
</P>
</TEXT>
