<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Customs Tax Collection Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- China's customs collected 44.72
billion yuan (5.39 billion US dollars) of taxes in the first half
of this year, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
The figure was up 3.84 billion yuan, or 9.4 percent more than
the same period last year, according to a statement from the
General Customs Administration.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months, China levied import duties worth 16.85
billion yuan, up 1.3 percent. Import taxes -- value-added tax and
consumption duties -- imposed in the period totaled 27.87 billion
yuan, a jump of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
China imported 63.05 billion US dollars' worth of goods in the
first half of this year, showing little change over last year.
But general trade imports dropped 8.9 percent to 17.38 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The statement attributed the increase in customs duty to the
central government's policy adjustment last year, which eliminated
certain tax preference on imports and thereby brought more
products into the taxable category. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin on Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
urged governments and departments concerned at all levels to
incorporate environmental protection goals into their annual as
well as medium- and long-term plans for social and economic
development.
</P>
<P>
The president stressed that no major construction project
should be launched without appropriate environmental protection
measures to go with it.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua published the full text of Jiang's speech at a national
forum on family planning and environmental protection held here
March 8.
</P>
<P>
Jiang pointed out that feasibility studies with a view to
environmental protection should be carried out prior to any
regional or natural resources development project. Effective
administrative procedures for environmental protection should be
established to make the decision-making process more scientific
and standardized. Investment in this aspect should also be
increased.
</P>
<P>
He said China has done a fairly good job in protecting its
environment amid rapid economic expansion since the reform and
opening-up policies were introduced some 18 years ago. Rapid
ecological deterioration has basically been kept at bay.
</P>
<P>
Facts have proved that the Chinese government's strategy to
coordinate economic development with environmental protection as
well as a series of policies to that end are both right and
effective.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that, with its national economy still
advancing at a pretty fast speed and population growing even
bigger, China's demands on natural resources will rise, too. Any
relaxation in our efforts to protect the environment would lead to
an increase in the volume of discharged pollutants and in the
scale of ecosystem damage, he said.
</P>
<P>
People will start to worry about the quality of their
environment when they can feed and cloth themselves. Therefore we
face great pressure as far as natural resources and environment
are concerned. The environmental situation is rather stern, which
means we have a lot to accomplish to protect the environment, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the Ninth Five-Year Plan and Long-Term Objectives
through the year 2010 for social and economic development set out
in explicit terms standards for environment protection in next 15
years: We must strive for basic containment of the worsening
environmental pollution and deteriorating ecosystem and for
improvement in environmental quality in a number of cities and
regions by the year 2000; and a fundamental reverse of ecosystem
deterioration and impressive improvement in rural and urban
environment by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
These are trans-century goals. Realization of these goals
requires not only efforts of the environmental protection
department and other departments, but also the concerted endeavors
of the whole Party and the whole people.
</P>
<P>
The legal framework to guide environmental protection work in
the socialist market economy should be perfected to provide
effective means for environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said departments in charge of environmental protection
should put in place unified supervision and administration in
accordance with the law. Judicial departments should strengthen
work in this regard and resolutely crack down on violators.
</P>
<P>
"The whole Party and people must join hands in creating a
better world for the coming generations," Jiang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Expands Metro Lines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's underground system is
being expanded in the eastern part with construction of an
arterial line running to the west where it will connect at
Fuxingmen.
</P>
<P>
the Fuxingmen to Bawangfen metro line running beneath many
important places will begin operation on September 28, 1999, said
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"It will alleviate traffic jams above ground and is a positive
move for prosperity of the eastern city," said Dong Xiaoli, an
official in charge of the construction project.
</P>
<P>
The line was designed to be 12.7 kilometers long with 11
stations. It stops at downtown shopping centers such as Xidan and
Wangfujing, and Fuxingmen where it will connect with the loop
line, said Li Shunli, an official with Beijing Mass Transit
Railway Corp (MTRB).
</P>
<P>
An estimated 550 million people will travel from Fuxingmen in
West Beijing to Bawangfen in the east by the end of 2,000. This is
well beyond the capacity of all above-ground mass transportation.
</P>
<P>
The construction budget for the line was 2.5 billion yuan (301
million US dollars) in 1990 when construction was kicked off by
MTRB.
</P>
<P>
With the soaring price of building materials, expenses hit six
billion yuan (722 million US dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Apart from a 162 million US dollars loan from the Japanese
Government, and a two billion yuan (240 million US dollars) loan
expected from the State Development Bank, the municipal government
is gathering money for the project and applying for preferential
policy in taxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
