<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Hotels Promote International Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's star-rated hotels have
improved service and management due to application of
international standards, today's China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
The city has 260 star-level hotels for overseas tourists, of
which 200 are State-owned and the rest are overseas-funded.
</P>
<P>
In order to establish a more efficient management system for
the hotel industry, the Beijing Municipal Tourism Administration
(BMTA) issued a series of market rules in keeping with
international practices and set up tourist guide marks in hotels
and scenic spots, the English daily said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the State-owned hotel facilities and services have
been brought up to international standards, the daily quoted a
BMTA spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
For example, Beijing Huadu Hotel, the first State-owned
three-star hotel in the early 1980s, has revised its service
standards and procedures in accordance with international
practices, to replace the out-dated methods followed under the
central planned economy.
</P>
<P>
"Just like the Jianguo Hotel -- the first overseas-funded hotel
in Beijing in the 1980s -- our hotel set up a new management
system, including personnel, financial affairs, facilities, and
services, to meet the needs of a market-oriented economy", the
newspaper quoted Liu Yuming, Huadu Hotel manager, as saying.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Huadu has successfully received three million
overseas and domestic tourists since it opened in 1982. It has
earned a total business income of 500 million yuan (60.2 million
US dollars) and turned out a total pretax-profit of 150 million
yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
