<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Personal Tax Revenue Soaring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- Revenue from personal income taxes
continued to increase rapidly in China in the first half of this
year, with steady economic growth and a tightening of tax
controls, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Personal income tax revenue to the end of last month soared by
42.5 percent on a year-on-year basis to 12.34 billion yuan (1.48
billion US dollars), fulfilling 51.4 percent of the annual target,
said Ye Lin'er, deputy division chief of the Income Taxation
Department of the State Taxation Administration.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate is far greater than that for total industrial
and commercial tax revenue, which recorded a 19.5 percent increase
over the previous year during the January-June period.
</P>
<P>
All the regions except for the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region
saw growth in the past six months, with Guangdong province in
South China, Shanghai and Beijing ranking among the top three
taxpaying regions in China.
</P>
<P>
Ye said the sharp increase was in line with the country's
stable economic development, which saw a 9.5 percent year-on-year
growth in the past six months.
</P>
<P>
The steady rise in individual incomes, at 2.2 percent for urban
residents and 3.3 percent for rural people during the past six
months, laid down a solid base for the progress of personal income
tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the high growth is that the taxation
authorities have intensified the management and supervision of tax
collection, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
He continued to say that this year's personal income tax yield
is projected to surpass 24 billion yuan, which will lift the ratio
of individual income tax to industrial and commercial tax to 3.45
percent from last year's three percent.
</P>
<P>
And the ratio may expand to five percent by the year 2000 and
ten percent by 2010, predicted the official.
</P>
<P>
Personal income tax revenue has continued to grow rapidly since
the Chinese Government started to enforce the new Personal Income
Tax Law in 1994, with revenue increasing on average by around 60
percent per year between 1994 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year personal income tax revenue amounted to 19.3 billion
yuan, an increase of 46.9 percent over the 1995 figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Search Is on For Wildlife in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 24 (Xinhua) -- After more than 100 years of
industrial development, are there still wild animals in Shanghai?
</P>
<P>
To answer this question, a scientific study was launched this
week. It is sponsored by the Shanghai Bureau of Agriculture and
Forestry, said today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Groups of researchers and university teachers and students were
sent to inspect 2,930 square kilometers of farmland in the
suburbs, 608 square kilometers in the intertidal zone in Wusong
and nearby lakes, with combined water-surface areas of 51 square
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The farmland was divided into 140 subareas, each three
kilometers long and 50 meters wide.
</P>
<P>
The researchers will focus on 287 kinds of wild animals,
including 60 under State protection, such as Chinese sturgeon,
otter, swan, mink and four-gill perch.
</P>
<P>
The field work is part of a national study and is expected to
be completed by 2000.
</P>
<P>
While preparing for the study, the wild animal protection
office of the Shanghai Bureau of Agriculture and Forestry teamed
up with Fudan University, East China Normal University and
Shanghai Museum of Nature Sciences to conduct a trial
investigation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
