<HEADLINE> European Season Kicks off without Incidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The European soccer season kicked
off with few surprises Wednesday as most of the big-gun favorites
came through with easy victories in the first-leg, first-round
qualifying games of the UEFA Cup and Champions Cup.
</P>
<P>
There were 35 games in all, and perhaps the biggest surprise
was the incident-free clash between Partizan Belgrade and Croatia
Zagreb in the Champions Cup.
</P>
<P>
Zagreb turned out to be the only national champion to be beaten
on Wednesday by losing 1-0 to the Serbs, although Romanian
champion Steaua Bucharest struggled for a 3-3 draw with Bulgaria's
CSKA Sofia.
</P>
<P>
Easy victories came through for Widzew Lodz of Poland, who
brought down the Azerberjain side Neftchi Baku 2-0, Rangers of
Scotland, who proved far too strong for their hosts Gi-Goto of the
Faroe Islands with a 5-0 victory, the Ukrainian powerhouse Dynamo
Kiev, who won 2-0 at home against Barry Town of Wales and
Georgia's Dynamo Tbsilis, who had a 3-0 away victory against
Crusaders of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
In UEFA Cup play, the Swiss side Grasshoppers offered a
lackluster 3-0 win against the amateur outfit of Coleraine from
Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Hadjuk Split, the Croatian league winners in 1995, began its
challenge for the UEFA Cup with a 4-1 victory against its hosts
Grevenmacher of Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The amateurs of Principat were Andorra's first-ever team to
compete in the UEFA Cup and they went down 8-0 to Scottish side
Dundee United.
</P>
<P>
Celtic of Scotland made a short trip to Wales to defeat Inter
Cable-Tel 3-0. 
</P>
</TEXT>
