<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jewell Sues New York Post for Libel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Richard Jewell, former prime
suspect for the Olympic bomb in Atlanta, sued the New York Post on
Wednesday for libel in its articles.
</P>
<P>
Lawyers for Jewell filed the lawsuit in the U.S. District Court
here, claiming that articles published by the newspaper after the
bomb explosion had false and defamatory statements.
</P>
<P>
On July 27, 1996, Jewell first noticed an unattended package at
the Centennial Olympic Park that was later found to contain the
bomb.
</P>
<P>
He was cleared of suspicion last November in the bombing which
claimed two fatalities and some 100 wounded in downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Jewell was under constant and intense scrutiny by
FBI agents, but the bombing remained unsolved up till now and with
little hope in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit alleged Jewell suffered permanent injury to his
reputation, public hatred and ridicule, seeking 5 million US
dollars in compensatory damages and 10 million in punitive damages
from the Post.
</P>
<P>
Early, Jewell reached legal settlements with CNN and NBC over
their coverage of the explosion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
