<HEADLINE> Ninety Seven of Top 100 Women Enter U.S. Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- World number one Martina Hingis
of Switzerland and two-time champion Monica Seles spearheaded the
97 of the top 100 ranked women players for next month's U.S. Open
Tennis Championships.
</P>
<P>
The most noticeable absentee is five-time champion Steffi Graf
of Germany, who was nursing from knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
Graf, currently ranked fifth in the world, is to be joined by
number 38 Wang Shi-Ting of Chinese Taipei and Marianne Werdel
Witmeyer of the United States, who is ranked 72nd.
</P>
<P>
Wang withdrew her entry before the deadline and Witmeyer, who
is currently eight-month pregnant, did not enter.
</P>
<P>
Hingis will be bidding for her third Grand Slam title of the
year. The 16-year-old captured titles at the Australian Open and
Wimbledon but lost to Iva Majoli in the French Open final.
</P>
<P>
Seles, the U.S. Open women's champion in 1991 and 1992, has
lost to Graf in each of the last two U.S. Open finals.
</P>
<P>
The only other former champion entered is Spain's Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario, who captured the title in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Other top players include Majoli, Wimbledon runner-up Jana
Novotna, 1995 Australian Open champion Mary Pierce, 1994 Wimbledon
champion Conchita Martinez, sixth-ranked Lindsay Davenport and
rising teenagers Anna Kournikova, Venus Williams and Mirjana Lucic.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Open will take place in New York from August 25
through September 7. 
</P>
