<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Notes Irregularities in Preferential Arrangements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- There exist many irregularities
in the implementation of the preferential tariff arrangements, an
essential part of the EU's development aid policy and an open
commercial policy, the European Commission said today.
</P>
<P>
In a communication adopted today, on the basis of the checks
carried out in 1996, the EU's executive agency estimated that
these irregularities were responsible for a loss of at least 220
million ECUs (around 285 million U.S. dollars), notably owing to
poor application of the rules of origin.
</P>
<P>
The commission has pinpointed three areas for action to remedy
these irregularities and facilitate recovery of duties from EU
operators, who are legally responsible for the correctness of the
import declaration.
</P>
<P>
The three areas are legislating the rules, making EU member
states shoulder their responsibilities and making the beneficiary
countries aware of the problem by, where necessary, adapting the
existing agreements.
</P>
<P>
Mario Monti, EU commissioner for customs, said that it was
absolutely necessary to restore confidence in these arrangements
to promote the development of the beneficiary countries by
facilitating their exports to the EU market while protecting the
EU's financial interests.
</P>
<P>
He added that abuse of these preferential arrangements would
give rise to deflections in trade which were harmful to the
economy of the partner countries and that of the union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
