<HEADLINE> Canada, US Discuss Salmon Dispute in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Officials from Canada and the
U.S. had "very good discussions" today on a bitter fishing dispute
that threatened their close relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with U.S. Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott and other officials, Canadian Foreign Minister
Lloyd Axworthy said, "We were able to look at the broad issues and
see how we can take steps forward."
</P>
<P>
Canadian fishermen insist that fishermen from the U.S. State of
Alaska have taken almost four times as much salmon this season as
allowed under a 1985 Pacific Salmon treaty.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. denied that it has breached any international
agreements.
</P>
<P>
"I think we both genuinely feel that the treaty is very
important," Axworthy told reporters. "To use that old expression,
we had very good discussions."
</P>
<P>
Last week, Canadian fishermen blockaded a U.S. ferry in a
harbor in Canada's British Columbia to protest the U.S.
over-fishing. 
</P>
