<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cocaine-Sentence Proposal Under Bipartisan Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
proposal to reduce differences in prison sentences for selling
crack and powdered cocaine came under bipartisan attack in
Congress today.
</P>
<P>
During the testimony by Clinton's drug-policy adviser Barry
McCaffrey today, a Republican member of the Senate Judiciary
Committee described the proposal as sending "the wrong signal" to
would-be drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno and McCaffrey Tuesday proposed
reducing the sentencing disparity for the two forms of cocaine to
a 10-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
The plan would impose mandatory five-year penalties for selling
25 grams of crack or 10 times as much powdered cocaine, 250 grams.
Current law requires five-year sentences for the sale of five
grams of crack or 500 grams of cocaine, a 100-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
Senator Spencer Abraham, a Republican from Michigan, noted
recent reports of increased drug use among American youths. Softer
sentences for possession of crack cocaine, he said, sent "the
wrong signal to young people."
</P>
<P>
He also said a new sentencing policy could reverse declines in
violent crime that have been attributed to a leveling-off of the
crack epidemic.
</P>
<P>
McCaffrey said the current system has an "injustice built into
it" and that removing the focus from low-level drug dealers could
free resources and allow officials to go after major traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Representative Maxine Waters, Democrat from California and
chairwoman of the Congressional Black Caucus, said the proposed
change to a 10-to-1 ratio remains unfair. She said the caucus
still wants a 1-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
Critics say the sentence structure is unfair to those dealing
in crack, which is cheaper but no worse than powder and is more
likely used by members of racial minorities. Others say crack is
more addictive because of its concentrated form and is more likely
to be associated with street violence.
</P>
<P>
"Any sentencing scheme that treats crack use and trafficking
more harshly than powder use and trafficking is not addressing
reality," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europeans, Americans Agree on Amending CFE Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Thirty countries to the Treaty
on the Conventional Forces in Europe (CFE) today reached a
framework agreement in Vienna to impose new and lower limits on
tanks and other non-nuclear weapons, a senior U.S. official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The CFE treaty, which was signed in 1990 and entered into force
in 1992, limits the number of tanks, artillery pieces, aircraft
and other non-nuclear arms European states can hold and where they
can be placed.
</P>
<P>
Robert Bell, a senior national security advisor to U.S.
President Bill Clinton, told reporters that the tentative accord
is a "remarkable example of the kind of cooperative effort" the
U.S. and Russia were making in arms control.
</P>
<P>
Bell said the agreement in principle included replacing the old
CFE treaty, which allowed one overall amount of equipment for NATO
and an equal amount for the countries of the now-defunct Warsaw
Pact, with a new system that sets national ceilings.
</P>
<P>
The 30 countries agreed a new treaty would set ceilings on the
amount of equipment, regardless of where the equipment comes from,
that any given country could station on its soil.
</P>
<P>
Bell said there was a significant amount of negotiation that
remained to be done in Vienna, where the CFE talks are being held,
and the negotiators hoped to have reached final agreement within a
year.
</P>
<P>
"At the end... all the national ceilings have been set, the
total amount of combat equipment that will be in Europe will be
significantly lower than the total amount that had been allowed by
the original 1990 treaty," Bell said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970724.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-23 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's King Gives Go-ahead for Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Hussein issued here
today a royal decree ordering the go-ahead for the parliamentary
elections scheduled for November, despite the claim by some
opposition parties to boycott them.
</P>
<P>
According to the first paragraph under Article 34 of the
Jordanian Constitution, polls will be conducted for the new
parliament as scheduled, Radio Jordan quoted the royal decree as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim Brotherhood, one of the main opposition parties in
Jordan, declared to boycott the elections earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Other opposition parties, including the Islamic Action Front
(IAF), the largest one in the country, have also considered to
follow suit.
</P>
<P>
A Jordanian government spokesman stressed earlier the
commitment of the government to holding free and fair
parliamentary elections as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the elections will be held as scheduled
in November no matter if the Muslim Brotherhood participates or
not.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's opposition parties now make up 23 seats in the
80-member Lower House of the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The multi-party system was revived in the kingdom in 1989 as
part of the political reform launched after the occurrence of
widespread riots caused by economic hardships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
