<HEADLINE> Kenyan Ruling Party Criticized Opposition's Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's ruling party Kenya
African National Union (KANU) announced tonight it is still
committed to constitutional reforms while criticizing that the
terms of the opposition for dialogue would only "hang the issue".
</P>
<P>
The parliament will be asked to enact a law on the
establishment of "a constitutional commission to look at the
question of legal and constitutional reforms," the Kenya
Television Network quoted a governmental statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party will discuss the issue with registered
opposition parties at such an institution, according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Some opposition parties have been denied to register for
goverenment's authorization despite the recent softening attitude
by the government to carry on constitutional reform.
</P>
<P>
The opposition's agenda intends to ignite public anger and
incitement, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's main opposition leaders agreed Wednesday that they
should negotiate with the government in unity on the issue of the
constitutional reforms and presented pre-conditions for the talks
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they vowed to continue to take mass actions "until
the government commits itself to bona fide dialogue." 
</P>
</TEXT>
