<HEADLINE> Canada Pledges Support for Bosnian Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government today
announced an additional 21.9 million U.S. dollars to support
reconstruction and peacebuilding activities in Bosnia and
Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Two-thirds of the money will be committed to social and
economic reconstruction, with the rest going toward peace
implementation activities.
</P>
<P>
While making the announcement, Canada's Foreign Affairs
Minister Lloyd Axworthy said his country believes that the
international community must continue to show its support for
reconstruction and peacebuilding in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"The international community's support, however, is conditional
on the Bosnian Parties' compliance with the December 1995 Peace
Agreement, including in the apprehension of persons indicted for
war crimes," he added.
</P>
<P>
Canada made the pledge on the first day of the Bosnia Donors'
Conference in Brussels, which was convened to coordinate Bosnian
reconstruction assistance and to raise 1.4 billion dollars in
pledges for 1997 reconstruction priorities.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian delegation is being led by Michael Berry, special
coordinator of reconstruction in the former Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
