<HEADLINE> US Dollar Higher on Comments by Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar hit another
six-year high against the mark and rose in most other dealings
today after top officials from the Bundesbank and Federal Reserve
signaled they don't oppose the U.S. currency's latest ascent.
</P>
<P>
The dollar reached an intraday high of 1.8325 marks, the
strongest since July 1991, before settling in New York at 1.8268
marks, up from 1.8240 marks Tuesday. The dollar cost 115.65 yen,
up from 115.15 yen. The pound cost 1.6804 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6790 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Later the dollar derived further strength from comments about
the U.S. economy by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, who
delivered the second day of his midyear economic report to
Congress. He called the combination of steady growth and low
inflation exceptional, with no mention of the dollar's strength as
a possible risk.
</P>
<P>
Other dollar rates in New York, compared with Tuesday: 1.4861
Swiss francs, up from 1.4829; 6.1554 French francs, up from 6.1436;
1,772.20 Italian lire, down from 1,772.90; 1.3815 Canadian dollars,
up from 1.3775. 
</P>
</TEXT>
