<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Delays Issuing Final Results of Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 23 (Xinhua) -- The Independent Elections Commission
(IECOM) of Liberia said this evening it would not release the final
results of Saturday's elections as scheduled today until tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
"We are still working on ballots counting and some of the ballots
have not arrived because of transportation problem," an IECOM official
reached by Xinhua said over the phone.
</P>
<P>
Due to the bad weather, the helicopters to bring electoral
officials and ballot boxes from various polling stations to the
capital Monrovia could not fly for most of the time, according to the
official who identified her name simply as Torbo.
</P>
<P>
The final results might come tomorrow, she said, refusing to give a
specific time. But a source in Monrovia said it might be in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Despite the delay, observers believe whatever the final results
could bring no dramatic change to the trend of the landslide victory of
former warlord Charles Taylor.
</P>
<P>
Latest figure provided by the Independent Elections Commission
shows that Taylor of the National Patriotic Party has won
356,548, or 75.4 percent, of the votes already counted.
</P>
<P>
Of the 472,863 valid votes released so far, his closest rival,
Unity Party's woman candidate Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf scored 45,195 or
9.53 percent, while Kromah, a former major warlord now running on the
platform of the All Liberian Coalition Party, received only 20,494, or
4.34 percent.
</P>
<P>
Results announced so far are collected from 1,344 polling stations
out of a total of 1,864 centers throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
About 710,00 Liberians registered as voters and some 90 percent of
them are believed to have taken part in Saturday's election.
</P>
<P>
To emerge as a president-elected, a candidate needs to win 51
percent of the total valid votes, otherwise a run-off will be held.
</P>
<P>
Although the final results are yet to come, Taylor's current score
is believed to make the run-off unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
While Taylor's supporters, most of whom young people, are
celebrating his preliminary victory, some politicians have reportedly
conveyed their congratulations to the former warlord.
</P>
<P>
Taylor launched a rebellion fighting against the late President of
Samuel Doe in December 1989, igniting a bloody civil war that
killed more than 150,000 people and displaced more others.
</P>
<P>
According to Liberia's election guidelines, the president-elected
will be installed on August 2, two weeks after the election, unless a
run-off is needed.
</P>
<P>
The election, which is widely recognized as free, fair and
transparent with minor irregularities, will also produce a new
parliament of 26 senators and 64 representatives.
</P>
<P>
The seats will be shared by parties according to the percentage of
votes they got.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
