<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Envoy Urges Senate Vote for NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 23 (Xinhua) -- Robert Hunter, U.S. ambassador
to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), today urged the
Senate to vote for the alliance's expansion.
</P>
<P>
Hunter made the strong plea at a State Department conference
for an all-out administration effort to persuade the Senate to
accept the expansion plan.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member alliance decided at its special summit in Madrid
earlier this month that it will invite Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic to join and its door will be open to new members.
</P>
<P>
"The idea of the United States Senate rejecting ratification...
is an intolerable thought," Hunter said. "The consequences if that
were to happen to the credibility of the United States not just in
NATO but globally would be I think without calculation."
</P>
<P>
Many senators oppose NATO's expansion plan, arguing that there
is no basis for the existence of the alliance since the Cold War
has ended and its rival Warsaw Pact has disappeared. They are also
concerned about the costs of the enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The ratification of the alliance's expansion plan needs to be
approved by a vote of two thirds majority in the Senate, which is
expected to take up the issue next spring.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to fail in that debate on ratification. That
must be an unthinkable idea," Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
The official estimated cost of the expansion for the U.S. is
150-200 million U.S. dollars a year over 10 years. Hunter argued
that it is a good bargain compared with some 4 trillion U.S.
dollar loss during World War II. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
